INSERT INTO `example` VALUES (84,'Example_1',1,80,'Show that given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\frac{t^2}{4} - \\frac{t}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{C}{t^2} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nit is a solution to the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		ty\' + 2y = t^2 - t + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y\'$ denotes the first derivative.','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\frac{t^2}{4} - \\frac{t}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{C}{t^2} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{t}{2} - \\frac{1}{3} - \\frac{2C}{t^3}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\require{cancel}\n		ty\' + 2y &= t^2 - t + 1 \\\\\n		t\\Big( \\frac{t}{2} - \\frac{1}{3} - \\frac{2C}{t^3} \\Big) + 2\\Big( \\frac{t^2}{4} - \\frac{t}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{C}{t^2} \\Big) &= t^2 - t + 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{t^2}{2} - \\frac{t}{3} - \\cancel{\\frac{2C}{t^2}} + \\frac{t^2}{2} - \\frac{2t}{3} + 1 + \\cancel{\\frac{2C}{t^2}} &= t^2 - t + 1 \\\\\n		t^2 - t + 1 &= t^2 - t + 1 \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is always true.'),(85,'Example_2',2,80,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^y y^{(7)} + \\sin(x)y^{(2)} = \\pi \n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y^{(n)}$ denotes the $n$th derivative, what is the order? Is it linear, and if so is it homogeneous?','Since the highest derivative to appear in the differential equation is the seventh derivative, the order is seven. It is not linear because of the exponential factor, especially worse that it is multiplied by one of the derivatives.'),(86,'Example_3',3,80,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = -\\frac{x}{y}\n	}$\n</div>\nshow that the curve:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + y^2 = 25\n	}$\n</div>\nis an implicit solution.','Using implicit differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + y^2 &= 25 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ x^2 + y^2 \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ 25 \\Big] \\\\\n		2x + 2y\\cdot\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		2y\\cdot\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -2x \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -\\frac{x}{y}\n	}$\n</div>'),(87,'Example_4',4,80,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + y = \\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y\'\'$ represents the second derivative, show that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = -\\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nis a solution.','First we need to find the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= -\\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ y \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ -\\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) \\Big] \\\\\n		y\' &= \\sin(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) - \\cos(x) \\cdot \\frac{\\sec(x)\\tan(x) + \\sec^2(x)}{\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\sin(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) - \\cos(x)\\sec(x) \\\\\n		y\' &= \\sin(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\sin(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) - 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ y\' \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\sin(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) - 1 \\Big] \\\\\n		y\'\' &= \\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) + \\sin(x) \\cdot \\frac{\\sec(x)\\tan(x) + \\sec^2(x)}{\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)} \\\\\n		y\'\' &= \\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) + \\sin(x)\\sec(x) \\\\\n		y\'\' &= \\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) + \\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are ready to verify the whether this function is a solution or not:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + y &= \\tan(x) \\\\\n		y\'\' &= \\tan(x) - y \\\\\n		\\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) + \\tan(x) &= \\tan(x) + \\cos(x)\\ln(\\sec(x) + \\tan(x)) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(88,'Example_5',5,80,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + 2xy = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nshow that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = e^{-x^2} \\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + Ce^{-x^2} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis a solution.','First we need the first derivative which requires taking the derivative of the integral. The integrand happens to not have a known closed form therefore, there must be a different way. Using the $\\textit{Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus}$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= e^{-x^2} \\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + Ce^{-x^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ y \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ e^{-x^2} \\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + Ce^{-x^2} \\Big] \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -2xe^{-x^2}\\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + e^{-x^2} \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt - 2Cxe^{-x^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -2xe^{-x^2}\\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + e^{-x^2} \\cdot e^{x^2} - 2Cxe^{-x^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -2xe^{-x^2}\\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + 1 - 2Cxe^{-x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation yields:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + 2xy &= 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 1 - 2xy \\\\\n		-2xe^{-x^2}\\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + 1 - 2Cxe^{-x^2} &= 1 - 2x\\Big[ e^{-x^2} \\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt + Ce^{-x^2} \\Big] \\\\\n		-2xe^{-x^2}\\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt - 2Cxe^{-x^2} &= -2xe^{-x^2} \\int_0^x e^{t^2} dt - 2Cxe^{-x^2} \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(89,'Example_6',6,80,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\sqrt{1 - y^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nfind the solution by determining the antiderivative and determine its interval of existance.','Essentially we need to use an integral to work backwards:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\sqrt{1 - y^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{dx}{dy} &= \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - y^2}} \\\\\n		\\int \\Big[ \\frac{dx}{dy} \\Big] dy &= \\int \\Big[ \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - y^2}} \\Big] dy \\\\\n		\\int dx &= \\int \\frac{dy}{\\sqrt{1 - y^2}} \\\\\n		x &= \\int \\frac{\\cos(\\theta)}{\\sqrt{1 - \\sin^2(\\theta)}} d\\theta \\\\\n		x &= \\int \\frac{\\cos(\\theta)}{\\sqrt{\\cos^2(\\theta)}} d\\theta \\\\\n		x &= \\int \\frac{\\cos(\\theta)}{|\\cos(\\theta)|} d\\theta \\\\\n		x &= \\int d\\theta \\\\\n		x &= \\theta + C \\\\\n		x &= \\arcsin(y) + C \\\\\n		0 &= \\arcsin(y) - x + C\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the absolute value can ignored because:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\arcsin(y) - x + C \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (0) &= \\frac{d}{dx} (\\arcsin(y) - x + C) \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{y\'}{\\sqrt{1 - y^2}} - 1 \\\\\n		y\' &= \\sqrt{1 - y^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nOn the other hand if we assumed that $cos(\\theta) < 0$, then the solution would take on the form and give rise to the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -\\arcsin(y) - x + C \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (0) &= \\frac{d}{dx} (-\\arcsin(y) - x + C) \\\\\n		0 &= -\\frac{y\'}{\\sqrt{1 - y^2}} - 1 \\\\\n		y\' &= -\\sqrt{1 - y^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is not the one we want. With this we have an implicit solution, but the explicit solution can also be determined:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\arcsin(y) - x + C \\\\\n		\\arcsin(y) &= x - C \\\\\n		y &= \\sin(x - C) \\\\\n		y &= \\sin(x + K)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		K = -C\n	}$\n</div>\ngets rid of the unneccesary negative sign. To look at the interval of existance, it is important to first take into account the domain of the differential equation. For the differential equation to exist, we must have it such that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		1 - y^2 &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		1 &\\geq y^2 \\\\\n		1 &\\geq \\sqrt{y^2} \\\\\n		1 &\\geq |y| \\\\\n		-1 \\leq &y \\leq 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich if you notice, also satisfies the implicit solution\'s domain since $\\arcsin$ is only defined for $y \\in [-1,1]$. As for $x$, it can be any real number since it does not give any issues in either the derivative or the general solution.'),(90,'Example_7',7,80,'Consider the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = e^{-x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nProvide reasoning why the solution to this differential equation must be an increasing function on the whole interval of existance. Next determine the differential equation\'s behavior at both ends of the $x$-axis. To finish up determine the concavity of the solution on the whole domain and use all of this information to draw out the graph of a single solution.','To understand the decreasing/increasing behavior of any given function, the behavior is always determined by the derivative. Since the derivative is given and is known to be always positive for all real numbers, the solution must be an increasing function on the whole interval of existance. To determine the given differential equation\'s behavior at the endpoints:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} e^{-x^2} = 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} e^{-x^2} = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nAs for the concavity of any given function, the behavior is determined by the second derivative. So to find the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= e^{-x^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} &= \\frac{d}{dx} e^{-x^2} \\\\\n		&= -2xe^{-x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNext we need the point(s) of inflection:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} \\\\\n		0 &= -2xe^{-x^2} \\\\\n		x &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if $x < 0$ the second derivative is positive, otherwise for $x > 0$ the second derivative is negative. This implies that the solution is going to be concave up for $x \\in (-\\infty,0)$ and concave down for $x \\in (0,\\infty)$. With all of this information, the solution will take on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Terminology/Example_7.png\">\n</div>\nNotice that the original function seems to always be positive which you can make sense of when considering that the derivative is always positive. A property of integrals tells us that given some function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\geq 0 \\hspace{.5cm} \\forall x \\in [a,b] \\implies \\int_a^b f(x) dx \\geq 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(91,'Example_8',8,80,'The graphs of members of the one-parameter family:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^3 + y^3 = 3Cxy \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.5cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nare called Folia of Descartes. Verify that this family is an implicit solution of the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{y(y^3 - 2x^3)}{x(2y^3 - x^3)}\n	}$\n</div>','The easiest way to verify is to just use implicit differentiation and solve for the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^3 + y^3 &= 3Cxy \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (x^3 + y^3) &= 3C \\frac{d}{dx} (xy) \\\\\n		3x^2 + 3y^2y\' &= 3C(y + xy\') \\\\\n		x^2 - Cy &= Cxy\' - y^2y\' \\\\\n		x^2 - Cy &= (Cx - y^2)y\' \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{x^2 - Cy}{Cx - y^2} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{x^2 - y \\cdot \\frac{x^3 + y^3}{3xy}}{x \\cdot \\frac{x^3 + y^3}{3xy} - y^2} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{x^2 - \\frac{x^2}{3} - \\frac{y^3}{3x}}{\\frac{x^3}{3y} + \\frac{y^2}{3} - y^2} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{\\frac{2x^2}{3} - \\frac{y^3}{3x}}{\\frac{x^3}{3y} - \\frac{2y^2}{3}} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{2x^2 - \\frac{y^3}{x}}{\\frac{x^3}{y} - 2y^2} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{y(2x^3 - y^3)}{x(x^3 - 2y^3)} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{y(y^3 - 2x^3)}{x(2y^3 - x^3)} \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that in order to arrive at the differential equation, I substituted the definition of $C$ in terms of the given solution. This has to be done in order to make sense since the parameter $C$ comes out of the integration and should only be a part of the general solution, not the differential equation.'),(92,'Example_9',9,80,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\sqrt{y^2 - 9}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine whether there exists a unique solution that goes through the different points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&(1,4) \\\\\n		&(5,-3) \\\\\n		&(2,-3) \\\\\n		&(-1,1)\n	}$\n</div>','In order to have a unique solution we need the derivative to exist at that point. For the first three points listed this holds true. As for the last point the derivative takes on imaginary values which we do not care about when we restrict ourselves to the real numbers, thus a unique solution over the real numbers will not exist.'),(93,'Example_10',10,80,'Write down the differential equation that models a situation where on the graph of $y = \\phi(x)$ the slope of the tangent line at a point $P(x,y)$ is the square of the distance from $P(x,y)$ to the origin.','The slope at any given point is going to be represented by $y\' = \\phi\'(x)$. As for the square of the distance from any point $P(x,y)$ to the origin, this can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d^2 = \\Big( \\sqrt{(x-0)^2 + (y-0)^2} \\Big)^2 = x^2 + y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow given that the slope is equal to the square of the distance, the differential equation is formally written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = x^2 + y^2\n	}$\n</div>'),(94,'Example_1',1,81,'Given the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 - 3y\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all the equilibrium points and graph the phase plot. Which equilibrium points are stable? Unstable? Semistable?','First to obtain all the equilibrium points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		y^2 - 3y &= 0 \\\\\n		y(y - 3) &= 0 \\\\\n		y &= 0, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$y\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty,0)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0,3)$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(3,\\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nand use this to graph the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Example_1.png\">\n</div>\nFor $y = 0$ since the vectors are pointing towards from both below and above, the equilibrium point is stable. On the other hand, for $y = 1$ the vectors are pointing away from both below and above, thus the equilibrium point is unstable.'),(95,'Example_2',2,81,'Given the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = (y - 2)^4\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all the equilibrium point(s) and graph the phase plot. Which equilibrium point(s) are stable? Unstable? Semistable?','First to obtain all the equilibrium points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		(y - 2)^4 &= 0 \\\\\n		y - 2 &= 0 \\\\\n		y &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$y\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty,2)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(2,\\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nand use this to graph the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Example_2.png\">\n</div>\nFor $y = 2$ the vectors below are pointing towards, but the vectors above are pointing away, thus the equilibrium point is semistable.'),(96,'Example_3',3,81,'Given the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y\\ln(y + 2)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all the equilibrium points and graph the phase plot. Which equilibrium points are stable? Unstable? Semistable?','First to obtain all the equilibrium points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		y\\ln(y + 2) &= 0 \\\\\n		y &= 0, -1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$y\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-2,-1)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-1,0)$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0,\\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nand use this to graph the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Example_3.png\">\n</div>\nFor $y = -1$ since the vectors are pointing towards from both below and above, the equilibrium point is stable. On the other hand, for $y = 0$ the vectors are pointing away from both below and above, thus the equilibrium point is unstable.'),(97,'Example_4',4,81,'Given the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{ye^y - 9y}{e^y}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all the equilibrium points and graph the phase plot. For different initial points $(-2,-5)$, $(0,1)$, and $(10,\\ln(9))$ determine what happens to each particular solution as $x \\rightarrow \\infty$.','First to obtain all the equilibrium points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{ye^y - 9y}{e^y} &= 0 \\\\\n		ye^y - 9e^y &= 0 \\\\\n		y(e^y - 9) &= 0 \\\\\n		y &= 0, \\ln(9)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$y\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty,0)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0,\\ln(9))$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(\\ln(9),\\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nand use this to graph the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Example_4.png\">\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of each particular solution at very large $x$ use the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(-2,-5): \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		(0,1): \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		(10,\\ln(9)): \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= \\ln(9)\n	}$\n</div>\nThe first point will follow the lowest region, the second point will follow the middle region, and the third point already lies on an equilibrium point and so it will stay there.'),(98,'Example_5',5,81,'Given the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2(4 - y^2)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all the equilibrium points and graph the phase plot. For different initial points $(-5,-4)$, $(7,0)$, and $(2,4)$ determine what happens to each particular solution as $x \\rightarrow \\infty$.','First to obtain all the equilibrium points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		y^2(4 - y^2) &= 0 \\\\\n		y^2(2 - y)(2 + y) &= 0 \\\\\n		y &= -2, 0, 2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$y\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty,-2)$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-2,0)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0,2)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(2,\\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nand use this to graph the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Example_5.png\">\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of each particular solution at very large $x$ use the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(-5,-4): \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= -\\infty \\\\\n		(7,0): \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		(2,4): \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nThe first point will follow the lowest region, the second point lies on an equilibrium point and so it will follow the middle region, and the third point will follow the highest region.'),(99,'Example_6',6,81,'Consider the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y - y\\sin(y)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all the equilibrium points and graph the phase plot for the region:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{R} = \\{ (x,y) \\in \\mathbb{R}^2 \\hspace{.1cm} | \\hspace{.1cm} -4\\pi \\leq x,y \\leq 4\\pi  \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWhich equilibrium points are stable? Unstable? Semistable?','First to obtain all the equilibrium points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		y - y\\sin(y) &= 0 \\\\\n		y(1 - \\sin(y)) &= 0 \\\\\n		y &= 0, \\frac{\\pi + 4k\\pi}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k \\in \\mathbb{Z}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative consider the fact that the only thing contributing to the sign of the derivative is the $y$ outside since the rest is always positive. So whenever $y < 0$ the derivative is negative and for $y > 0$ it is positive. Using this to graph the phase plot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Example_6.png\">\n</div>\nFor $y = 0$ the vectors below and above are pointing away, thus the equilibrium point is unstable. All other equilibrium points are semistable because one side will lean towards, while the other away since the direction is going to stay downwards for the region below $y = 0$ and upwards for the region above.'),(100,'Example_7',7,81,'The velocity, $v$, of a body of mass $m$ that is falling under the influence of gravity can be modeled by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		m\\frac{dv}{dt} = mg - kv\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $g$ is the acceleration due to gravity and $k$ is some positive constant. Because the term $-kv$ represents air resistance, the velocity of a body falling from a great height does not increase without bound as time $t$ increases. Use this to determine the terminal velocity of the body at large $t$.','First to obtain the equilibrium point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dv}{dt} &= 0 \\\\\n		g - \\frac{k}{m}v &= 0 \\\\\n		v &= \\frac{mg}{k}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$v\'(t)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\Big( 0, \\frac{mg}{k} \\Big)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\Big( \\frac{mg}{k}, \\infty \\Big)$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nFor the single equilibrium point, both below and above the vectors point towards. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{t \\rightarrow \\infty} v(t) = \\frac{mg}{k}\n	}$\n</div>\nfor any initial condition.'),(101,'Example_8',8,81,'What can be said about an autonomous system that does not have any equilibrium points? Provide an example of a function and its corresponding autonomous system.','Any function that does not have any equilibrium points is one whose slope does not change signs. For example consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is known to always have a positive slope and is a constantly increasing function. Taking the derivative of both sides results in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= e^x \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} e^x \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= e^x \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= y(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nin an autonomous system that is known to not have any equilibrium points. So any function without equilibrium points is one that will either keep on increasing or decreasing depending upon the derivative.'),(102,'Example_9',9,81,'We know from experience that hot objects cool down to the temperature of their surroundings and cold objects warm up to the temperature of their surroundings. Newton\'s law of cooling says more specifically that the temperature difference between an object and its surroundings changes at a rate proportional to the difference between the temperature of the object and that of its surroundings. Let $T(t)$ be the temperature of an object and $R(t)$ the temperature of the room in which it resides, where $t$ is measured in minutes since the object was placed in the room. Write a differential equation that models the temperature dynamics and identify its equilibrium point. After writing down the general differential equation suppose the temperature of the room is held constant at $65^\\circ$ Celsius and a cup of hot mulled apple cider with a temperature of $180^\\circ$ Celsius is placed in the room. What is the new differential equation?','Given that the rate of change of the difference between $T(t)$ and $R(t)$ is proportional to the difference between $T(t)$ and $R(t)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt}(T - R) = k(T - R)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the equilibrium point occurs at $T = R$. Now given the temperature of the room, the differential equation becomes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt}(T - 65) = k(T - 65)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $T(0) = 180$ is the initial condition.'),(103,'Example_10',10,81,'Prove that any autonomous differential equation is independent of translations related to the independent variable. As an extension, deduce the fix needed to the differential equation if the independent variable is a multiplied by some factor $\\alpha$.','Assuming that the autonomous system takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) = f(y(x))\n	}$\n</div>\na translation in the independent variable would mean that a new solution would take on the form $y(x - k)$, which implies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} y(x - k) &= y\'(x - k)\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the new differential equation becomes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x - k) = f(y(x - k))\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is not any different than the original one. Now if instead we are looking at a solution of the form $y(\\alpha x)$, this implies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} y(\\alpha x) &= \\alpha y\'(\\alpha x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the new differential equation becomes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(\\alpha x) = \\frac{1}{\\alpha} f(y(\\alpha x))\n	}$\n</div>'),(104,'Example_1',1,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2\n	}$\n</div>\ndraw out the slope field.','Since the derivative is independent of $x$, each vertical cross section will be identical and produce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_1.png\">\n</div>'),(105,'Example_2',2,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = x(x-1)\n	}$\n</div>\ndraw out the slope field.','Since the derivative is independent of $y$, each horizontal cross section will be identical and produce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_2.png\">\n</div>'),(106,'Example_3',3,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = xy\n	}$\n</div>\ndraw out the slope field.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_3.png\">\n</div>'),(107,'Example_4',4,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y\n	}$\n</div>\ndraw out the slope field.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_4.png\">\n</div>'),(108,'Example_5',5,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y\\cos(y)\n	}$\n</div>\ndraw out the slope field.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_5.png\">\n</div>'),(109,'Example_6',6,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = x\n	}$\n</div>\nfind the general solution by determining the antiderivative and sketch some of the solution curves.','In order to find the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= \\int \\frac{dy}{dx} dx \\\\\n		&= \\int x dx \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2}x^2 + C\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the solution curves take on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_6.png\">\n</div>\nwhich is a family of parabolas with different $y$-intercepts.'),(110,'Example_7',7,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = xy\n	}$\n</div>\nhas the general solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = Ce^{\\frac{x^2}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nuse this to sketch some of the solution curves.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_7.png\">\n</div>'),(111,'Example_8',8,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nhas the general solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\tan(x + C)\n	}$\n</div>\nuse this to sketch some of the solution curves.','This family of curves basically consists of taking the regular graph of $\\tan(x)$ and accounting for horizontal shifts to the left and right:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_8.png\">\n</div>'),(112,'Example_9',9,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nfind the general solution by determining the antiderivative and sketch some of the solution curves.','In order to find the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= \\int \\frac{dy}{dx} dx \\\\\n		&= \\int \\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		&= -\\cos(x) + C\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the solution curves take on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_9.png\">\n</div>\nwhich is a family of cosine curves with different vertical shifts.'),(113,'Example_10',10,82,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = xe^x\n	}$\n</div>\nfind the general solution by determining the antiderivative and sketch some of the solution curves.','In order to find the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= \\int \\frac{dy}{dx} dx \\\\\n		&= \\int xe^x dx \\\\\n		&= xe^x - \\int e^x dx \\\\\n		&= xe^x - e^x + C \\\\\n		&= (x - 1)e^x + C\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the solution curves take on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Example_10.png\">\n</div>'),(114,'Example_1',1,83,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = \\frac{3x^2 + 4x - 4}{2y - 4}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = 3$.','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{3x^2 + 4x - 4}{2y - 4} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{3x^2 + 4x - 4}{2y - 4} \\\\\n		(2y - 4) dy &= (3x^2 + 4x - 4) dx \\\\\n		\\int (2y - 4) dy &= \\int (3x^2 + 4x - 4) dx \\\\\n		y^2 - 4y &= x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x + C \\\\\n		y^2 - 4y - x^3 - 2x^2 + 4x &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above solution could have been put in explicit form, but that would involve using square roots, which I prefer to avoid for the time being. Now to satisfy the intial value we are given that $y(1) = 3$ which is the same as saying that $(1,3)$ is a point that must lie on the curve of the solution: \n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= y^2 - 4y - x^3 - 2x^2 + 4x \\\\\n		&= (3)^2 - 4(3) - (1)^3 - 2(1)^2 + 4(1) \\\\\n		&= -2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^2 - 4y - x^3 - 2x^2 + 4x = -2\n	}$\n</div>\nIn case an implicit solution does not satisfy you, here is how the explicit solution can be found using the quadratic formula:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-2 &= y^2 - 4y - x^3 - 2x^2 + 4x \\\\\n		0 &= (y^2) - (4y) - (x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x - 2) \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{4 \\pm \\sqrt{16 + 4(x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x - 2)}}{2} \\\\\n		y &= 2 \\pm \\sqrt{x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow a singular questions remains: which root to pick? This can only be checked if an initial value is given. In this case the point $(1,3)$ must lie on the curve:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(1) &= 2 + \\sqrt{(1)^3 + 2(1)^2 - 4(1) + 2} = 2 + \\sqrt{1} = 3 \\\\\n		y(1) &= 2 - \\sqrt{(1)^3 + 2(1)^2 - 4(1) + 2} = 2 - \\sqrt{1} = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the positive root produces the needed result, it is the correct solution in explicit form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = 2 + \\sqrt{x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x + 2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(115,'Example_2',2,83,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = e^{-y}(2x - 4)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(5) = 0$.','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= e^{-y}(2x - 4) \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= e^{-y}(2x - 4) \\\\\n		e^y dy &= (2x - 4) dx \\\\\n		\\int e^y dy &= \\int (2x - 4) dx \\\\\n		e^y &= x^2 - 4x + C \\\\\n		e^y - x^2 + 4x &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if we want to, finding the explicit solution can easily be achieved from the implicit solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^y - x^2 + 4x &= C \\\\\n		e^y &= x^2 - 4x + C \\\\\n		y &= \\ln(x^2 - 4x + C)\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off the initial value has to be used to determine the value of the constant of integration:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y(5) \\\\\n		0 &= \\ln((5)^2 - 4(5) + C) \\\\\n		0 &= \\ln(5 + C) \\\\\n		1 &= 5 + C \\\\\n		C &= -4\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\ln(x^2 - 4x - 4)\n	}$\n</div>'),(116,'Example_3',3,83,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{y^2 - 1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = 2$.','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{y^2 + 1}{x} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{y^2 + 1} &= \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dy}{y^2 + 1} &= \\int \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) &= \\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) - \\ln|x| &= C					\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if we want to, finding the explicit solution can easily be achieved from the implicit solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\arctan(y) - \\ln|x| &= C \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) &= \\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		y &= \\tan(\\ln|x| + C)\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off the initial value has to be used to determine the value of the constant of integration:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2 &= y(1) \\\\\n		2 &= \\tan(\\ln|1| + C) \\\\\n		2 &= \\tan(C) \\\\\n		C &= \\arctan(2)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\tan(\\ln|x| + \\arctan(2))\n	}$\n</div>'),(117,'Example_4',4,83,'Find all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} = 1 + \\frac{1}{y^2}\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= 1 + \\frac{1}{y^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{1 + y^{-2}} &= dt \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dy}{1 + y^{-2}} &= \\int dt \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{y^2}{y^2 + 1} dy &= t + C \\\\\n		\\int \\Big( 1 - \\frac{1}{y^2 + 1} \\Big) dy &= t + C \\\\\n		y - \\arctan(y) &= t + C \\\\\n		y - \\arctan(y) - t &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above scenario does not provide any simple means of obtaining the explicit solution, therefore just stick with the implicit solution.'),(118,'Example_5',5,83,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} = 1 + t^2 + y^2 + t^2y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = 1$.','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= 1 + t^2 + y^2 + t^2y^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= (1 + t^2) + (1 + t^2)y^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= (1 + y^2)(1 + t^2) \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{1 + y^2} &= (1 + t^2) dt \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dy}{1 + y^2} &= \\int (1 + t^2) dt \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) &= t + \\frac{1}{3}t^3 + C \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) - t - \\frac{1}{3}t^3 &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if we want to, finding the explicit solution can easily be achieved from the implicit solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\arctan(y) - t - \\frac{1}{3}t^3 &= C \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) &= t + \\frac{1}{3}t^3 + C \\\\\n		y &= \\tan\\Big( t + \\frac{1}{3}t^3 + C \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off the initial value has to be used to determine the value of the constant of integration:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		1 &= y(0) \\\\\n		1 &= \\tan\\Big( 0 + \\frac{1}{3}(0)^3 + C \\Big) \\\\\n		1 &= \\tan(C) \\\\\n		C &= \\frac{\\pi}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\tan\\Big( t + \\frac{1}{3}t^3 + \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(119,'Example_6',6,83,'Find all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		T\' = k(T - T_0)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $k, T_0 \\in \\mathbb{R}$.','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		T\' &= k(T - T_0) \\\\\n		\\frac{dT}{dt} &= k(T - T_0) \\\\\n		\\frac{dT}{T - T_0} &= k dt \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dT}{T - T_0} &= \\int k dt \\\\\n		\\ln|T - T_0| &= kt + C \\\\\n		\\ln|T - T_0| - kt &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nIn case an implicit solution does not satisfy you, here is how the explicit solution can be found using simple algebraic manipulation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln|T - T_0| - kt &= C \\\\\n		\\ln|T - T_0| &= kt + C \\\\\n		T - T_0 &= e^{kt + C} \\\\\n		T &= e^{kt}e^C + T_0 \\\\\n		T &= De^{kt} + T_0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $D = e^C$ is a more comfortable way of writing down the constant of integration.'),(120,'Example_7',7,83,'Find all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} - x^2y^2 = x^2\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} - x^2y^2 &= x^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= x^2y^2 + x^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= x^2(y^2 + 1) \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{y^2 + 1} &= x^2 dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dy}{y^2 + 1} &= \\int x^2 dx \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) &= \\frac{x^3}{3} + C \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) - \\frac{x^3}{3} &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above solution could have been put in explicit form using simple algebraic manipulation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\arctan(y) - \\frac{x^3}{3} &= C \\\\\n		\\arctan(y) &= \\frac{x^3}{3} + C \\\\\n		y &= \\tan\\Big( \\frac{x^3}{3} + C \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(121,'Example_8',8,83,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} = \\frac{4\\sin(2t)}{y}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = 1$.','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= \\frac{4\\sin(2t)}{y} \\\\\n		y dy &= 4\\sin(2t) dt \\\\\n		\\int y dy &= \\int 4\\sin(2t) dt \\\\\n		\\frac{y^2}{2} &= -2\\cos(2t) + C \\\\\n		\\frac{y^2}{2} + 2\\cos(2t) &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above solution could have been put in explicit form, but that would involve using square roots, which I prefer to avoid for the time being. Now to satisfy the intial value we are given that $y(0) = 1$ which is the same as saying that $(0,1)$ is a point that must lie on the curve of the solution: \n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\frac{y^2}{2} + 2\\cos(2t) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(1)^2}{2} + 2\\cos(2(0)) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2} + 2 \\\\\n		&= \\frac{5}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{y^2}{2} + 2\\cos(2t) = \\frac{5}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nIn case an implicit solution does not satisfy you, here is how the explicit solution can be found:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{y^2}{2} + 2\\cos(2t) &= \\frac{5}{2} \\\\\n		\\frac{y^2}{2} &= \\frac{5}{2} - 2\\cos(2t) \\\\\n		y^2 &= 5 - 4\\cos(2t) \\\\\n		y &= \\pm \\sqrt{5 - 4\\cos(2t)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow a singular questions remains: which root to pick? This can only be checked if an initial value is given. In this case the point $(0,1)$ must lie on the curve:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) &= \\sqrt{5 - 4\\cos(2(0))} = \\sqrt{5 - 4} = 1 \\\\\n		y(0) &= -\\sqrt{5 - 4\\cos(2(0))} = -\\sqrt{5 - 4} = -1\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the positive root produces the needed result, it is the correct solution in explicit form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\sqrt{5 - 4\\cos(2t)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(122,'Example_9',9,83,'Find all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\ln(y)}\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\ln(y)} \\\\\n		\\ln(y) dy &= \\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int \\ln(y) dy &= \\int \\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		y\\ln(y) - y &= -\\cos(x) + C \\\\\n		y\\ln(y) - y + \\cos(x) &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above solution does not provide any simple means of obtaining an explicit solution, therefore just stick with the implicit solution.'),(123,'Example_10',10,83,'Find all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2y\' = e^{x + y + 3}\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function is separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2y\' &= e^{x + y + 3} \\\\\n		2\\frac{dy}{dx} &= e^{x + 3}e^{y} \\\\\n		2e^{-y} dy &= e^{x + 3} dx \\\\\n		\\int 2e^{-y} dy &= \\int e^{x + 3} dx \\\\\n		-2e^{-y} &= e^{x + 3} + C \\\\\n		2e^{-y} + e^{x + 3} &= -C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo put the solution in explicit form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2e^{-y} + e^{x + 3} &= -C \\\\\n		2e^{-y} &= -e^{x + 3} - C \\\\\n		e^{-y} &= \\frac{-e^{x + 3} - C}{2} \\\\\n		-y &= \\ln\\Big( \\frac{-e^{x + 3} - C}{2} \\Big) \\\\\n		y &= \\ln\\Big( -\\frac{2}{e^{x + 3} + C} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(124,'Example_1',1,84,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		ty\' + 2y = t^2 - t + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = \\frac{1}{2}$.','First rearranging gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		ty\' + 2y &= t^2 - t + 1 \\\\\n		y\' + \\frac{2}{t}y &= t - 1 + \\frac{1}{t} \n	}$\n</div>\nNow this is in the form of a first order linear differential equation. Next the integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int \\frac{2}{t} dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{2\\ln|t|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|t|^2)} \\\\\n		&= (|t|)^2 \\\\\n		&= t^2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow multiplying the equation throughout by the integrating factor gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + \\frac{2}{t}y &= t - 1 + \\frac{1}{t} \\\\\n		t^2y\' + 2ty &= t^3 - t^2 + t \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (t^2 y) &= t^3 - t^2 + t \\\\\n		d(t^2 y) &= (t^3 - t^2 + t) dt \\\\\n		\\int d(t^2 y) &= \\int (t^3 - t^2 + t) dt \\\\\n		t^2 y &= \\frac{t^4}{4} - \\frac{t^3}{3} + \\frac{t^2}{2} + C \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{t^2}{4} - \\frac{t}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{C}{t^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the value of $C$ use the initial value given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{1}{2} &= y(1) \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2} &= \\frac{(1)^2}{4} - \\frac{(1)}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{C}{(1)^2} \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{3} + C \\\\\n		C &= \\frac{1}{12}\n	}$\n</div>\nso that the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\frac{t^2}{4} - \\frac{t}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{12t^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(125,'Example_2',2,84,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		ty\' - 2y = t^5\\sin(2t) - t^3 + 4t^4\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(\\pi) = \\frac{3}{2}\\pi^4$.','First rearranging gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		ty\' - 2y &= t^5\\sin(2t) - t^3 + 4t^4 \\\\\n		y\' - \\frac{2}{t}y &= t^4\\sin(2t) - t^2 + 4t^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow this is in the form of a first order linear differential equation. Next the integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int -\\frac{2}{t} dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{-2\\ln|t|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|t|^{-2})} \\\\\n		&= (|t|)^{-2} \\\\\n		&= t^{-2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow multiplying the equation throughout by the integrating factor gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' - \\frac{2}{t}y &= t^4\\sin(2t) - t^2 + 4t^3 \\\\\n		t^{-2}y\' - 2t^{-3}y &= t^2\\sin(2t) - 1 + 4t \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (t^{-2}y) &= t^2\\sin(2t) - 1 + 4t \\\\\n		d(t^{-2}y) &= (t^2\\sin(2t) - 1 + 4t) dt \\\\\n		\\int d(t^{-2}y) &= \\int (t^2\\sin(2t) - 1 + 4t) dt \\\\\n		t^{-2}y &= \\frac{1}{4}((1 - 2t^2)\\cos(2t) + 2t\\sin(2t)) - t + 2t^2 + C \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{1}{4}((t^2 - 2t^4)\\cos(2t) + 2t^3\\sin(2t)) - t^3 + 2t^4 + Ct^2\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the value of $C$ use the initial value given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{3}{2}\\pi^4 &= y(\\pi) \\\\\n		\\frac{3}{2}\\pi^4 &= \\frac{1}{4}(((\\pi)^2 - 2(\\pi)^4)\\cos(2\\pi) + 2(\\pi)^3\\sin(2\\pi)) - (\\pi)^3 + 2(\\pi)^4 + C(\\pi)^2 \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{1}{4}\\pi^2 - \\pi^3 + C\\pi^2 \\\\\n		C &= \\pi - \\frac{1}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nso that the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\frac{1}{4}((t^2 - 2t^4)\\cos(2t) + 2t^3\\sin(2t)) - t^3 + 2t^4 + \\Big( \\pi - \\frac{1}{4} \\Big)t^2\n	}$\n</div>'),(126,'Example_3',3,84,'Solve the following differential equation for $t > 0$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2t\\frac{dy}{dt} - y = t + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(2) = 4$.','First rearranging gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2t\\frac{dy}{dt} - y &= t + 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} - \\frac{1}{2t}y = \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{2t}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow this is in the form of a first order linear differential equation. Next the integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int -\\frac{1}{2t} dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{-\\frac{1}{2}\\ln|t|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|t|^{-\\frac{1}{2}})} \\\\\n		&= |t|^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\\n		&= t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is only allowed since $t > 0$ is given as a condition. Now multiplying the equation throughout by the integrating factor gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}\\frac{dy}{dt} - \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{3}{2}}y &= \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{3}{2}} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} \\Big( t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}y \\Big) &= \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{3}{2}} \\\\\n		d\\Big( t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}y \\Big) &= \\Big( \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{3}{2}} \\Big) dt \\\\\n		\\int d\\Big( t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}y \\Big) &= \\int \\Big( \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\frac{1}{2}t^{-\\frac{3}{2}} \\Big) dt \\\\\n		t^{-\\frac{1}{2}}y &= t^\\frac{1}{2} - t^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + C \\\\\n		y &= t - 1 + Ct^\\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the value of $C$ use the initial value given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4 &= y(2) \\\\\n		4 &= (2) - 1 + C(2)^\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		3 &= \\sqrt{2}C \\\\\n		C &= \\frac{3}{\\sqrt{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nso that the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = t - 1 + 3\\sqrt{\\frac{t}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(127,'Example_4',4,84,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\cos^2(t)\\sin(t)y\' = -\\cos^3(t)y + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) = 0$.','First rearranging gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\cos^2(t)\\sin(t)y\' &= -\\cos^3(t)y + 1 \\\\\n		\\cos^2(t)\\sin(t)y\' + \\cos^3(t)y &= 1 \\\\\n		y\' + \\frac{\\cos(t)}{\\sin(t)}y &= \\frac{1}{\\cos^2(t)\\sin(t)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow this is in the form of a first order linear differential equation. Next the integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int \\frac{\\cos(t)}{\\sin(t)} dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln|\\sin(t)|} \\\\\n		&= |\\sin(t)| \\\\\n		&= \\sin(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the absolute value is allowed to be dropped since any multiple of the integrating factor is also an integrating factor. So putting a negative sign will not change the outcome. Now multiplying the equation throughout by the integrating factor gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(t)y\' + \\cos(t)y &= \\frac{1}{\\cos^2(t)} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (\\sin(t)y) &= \\sec^2(t) \\\\\n		d(\\sin(t)y) &= \\sec^2(t) dt \\\\\n		\\int d(\\sin(t)y) &= \\int \\sec^2(t) dt \\\\\n		\\sin(t)y &= \\tan(t) + C \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{\\tan(t)}{\\sin(t)} + \\frac{C}{\\sin(t)} \\\\\n		y &= \\sec(t) + C\\csc(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the value of $C$ use the initial value given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) \\\\\n		0 &= \\sec\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) + C\\csc\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) \\\\\n		0 &= \\sqrt{2} + C\\sqrt{2} \\\\\n		C &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nso that the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\sec(t) - \\csc(t)\n	}$\n</div>'),(128,'Example_5',5,84,'Determine all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		t\\ln(t)\\frac{dr}{dt} + r = te^t\n	}$\n</div>','First rearranging gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		t\\ln(t)\\frac{dr}{dt} + r &= te^t \\\\\n		\\frac{dr}{dt} + \\frac{1}{t\\ln(t)}r &= \\frac{e^t}{\\ln(t)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow this is in the form of a first order linear differential equation. Next the integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int \\frac{1}{t\\ln(t)} dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln|\\ln(t)|} \\\\\n		&= |\\ln(t)| \\\\\n		&= \\ln(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since the original domain of the function to begin with is $(0,\\infty)$. Even if $t \\in (0,1)$, putting a negative sign in front will not change the result. Now multiplying the equation throughout by the integrating factor gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(t)\\frac{dr}{dt} + \\frac{1}{t}r &= e^t \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt}(\\ln(t)r) &= e^t \\\\\n		d(\\ln(t)r) &= e^t dt \\\\\n		\\int d(\\ln(t)r) &= \\int e^t dt \\\\\n		\\ln(t)r &= e^t + C \\\\\n		r &= \\frac{e^t + C}{\\ln(t)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(129,'Example_6',6,84,'Determine all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2y\' + 2xy = \\cos^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nOnce the family of solutions is obtained, plot the curves for $C = -2, -1, 0, 1, 2$. From the graph what is the behavior of $y(x)$ as $x \\rightarrow \\infty$ or $x \\rightarrow -\\infty$? Justify why this makes sense.','Take notice that the left hand side is already in the form of a product rule. Just proceed to solving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2y\' + 2xy &= \\cos^2(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(x^2y) &= \\cos^2(x) \\\\\n		d(x^2y) &= \\cos^2(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int d(x^2y) &= \\int \\cos^2(x) dx \\\\\n		x^2y &= \\frac{1}{2}(x + \\sin(x)\\cos(x)) + C \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{1}{2x^2}(x + \\sin(x)\\cos(x)) + \\frac{C}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the family of curves:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Linear/Example_6.png\">\n</div>\nThe graph seems to point to the fact that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} y(x) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nTo make sense of this, take the limits on the general solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\Big( \\frac{1}{2x^2}(x + \\sin(x)\\cos(x)) + \\frac{C}{x^2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x + \\sin(x)\\cos(x)}{2x^2} + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{C}{x^2} \\\\\n		&= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} y(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\Big( \\frac{1}{2x^2}(x + \\sin(x)\\cos(x)) + \\frac{C}{x^2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{x + \\sin(x)\\cos(x)}{2x^2} + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{C}{x^2} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSo no matter the value of $C$, the end behavior is consistent for the whole family.'),(130,'Example_7',7,84,'Determine all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		xy\' = y + x^2\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nOnce the family of solutions is obtained, plot the curves for $C = -2, -1, 0, 1, 2$. Do all the plots feature a common intersection point?','First rearranging gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		xy\' &= y + x^2\\sin(x) \\\\\n		xy\' - y &= x^2\\sin(x) \\\\\n		y\' - x^{-1}y &= x\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow this is in the form of a first order linear differential equation. Next the integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int -x^{-1} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x|^{-1})} \\\\\n		&= |x|^{-1} \\\\\n		&= x^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since multiplying by a negative gives the same result. Now multiplying the equation throughout by the integrating factor gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^{-1}y\' - x^{-2}y &= \\sin(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(x^{-1}y) &= \\sin(x) \\\\\n		d(x^{-1}y) &= \\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int d(x^{-1}y) &= \\int \\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		x^{-1}y &= -\\cos(x) + C \\\\\n		y &= -x\\cos(x) + Cx\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the family of curves:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Linear/Example_7.png\">\n</div>\nThe graph seems to point to the fact that all the different plots intersect at the origin.'),(131,'Example_8',8,84,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)}\\Big( y_0 + \\int_{x_0}^x \\mu(s)q(s) ds \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nis a solution to the first order linear differential equation where $y(x_0) = y_0$ and $\\mu(x)$ is the integrating factor by differentiating both sides. What is the difference between this solution and the one found in the notes?','To take the derivative of both sides use the product rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)}\\Big( y_0 + \\int_{x_0}^x \\mu(s)q(s) ds \\Big) \\Big] \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{\\mu\'(x)}{\\mu^2(x)}\\Big( y_0 + \\int_{x_0}^x \\mu(s)q(s) ds \\Big) + \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)} \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx}\\Big( y_0 + \\int_{x_0}^x \\mu(s)q(s) ds \\Big) \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{\\mu\'(x)}{\\mu(x)} \\cdot \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)}\\Big( y_0 + \\int_{x_0}^x \\mu(s)q(s) ds \\Big) + \\frac{\\mu(x)q(x)}{\\mu(x)} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{p(x)\\mu(x)}{\\mu(x)}y + q(x) \\\\\n		&= -p(x)y + q(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nThis form of the solution specifically uses the fact that there is some initial condition. In order to use definite integrals, one of the boundaries has to represent the initial condition, otherwise there is not enough information. So generally when there may not be more information, an indefinite integral is utilized to account for the family of solutions.'),(132,'Example_9',9,84,'Determine all solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w\'\' + p(x)w\' = q(x)\n	}$\n</div>','First make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= w\' \\\\\n		y\' &= w\'\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + p(x)y &= q(x) \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)}(L(x) + C)\n	}$\n</div>\nthe general solution obtained in the notes. Now to solve for $w$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dw}{dx} &= y(x) \\\\\n		dw &= y(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int dw &= \\int \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)}(L(x) + C) dx \\\\\n		w(x) &= J(x) + D\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		J(x) = \\int \\frac{1}{\\mu(x)}(L(x) + C) dx \\hspace{.5cm}\n	}$\n</div>\nand $D$ is the constant of integration coming out of the second integral.'),(133,'Example_10',10,84,'Determine a continuous solution to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + P(x)y = 4x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		P(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			2 & 0 \\leq x \\leq 1 \\\\\n			-\\frac{2}{x} & x > 1\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nand $y(0) = 3$.','To approach this, just consider the different cases separately. First for $x \\in [0,1]$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + 2y = 4x\n	}$\n</div>\nhas the integrating factor:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int P(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int 2 dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich leads to the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + 2y &= 4x \\\\\n		e^{2x}y\' + 2e^{2x}y &= 4xe^{2x} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (e^{2x}y) &= 4xe^{2x} \\\\\n		d(e^{2x}y) &= 4xe^{2x} dx \\\\\n		\\int d(e^{2x}y) &= \\int 4xe^{2x} dx \\\\\n		e^{2x}y &= e^{2x}(2x - 1) + C_1 \\\\\n		y &= 2x - 1 + C_1e^{-2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for $x \\in (1, \\infty)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' - \\frac{2}{x}y = 4x\n	}$\n</div>\nhas the integrating factor:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int P(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -\\frac{2}{x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-2\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x|^{-2})} \\\\\n		&= |x|^{-2} \\\\\n		&= x^{-2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich leads to the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' - \\frac{2}{x}y &= 4x \\\\\n		x^{-2}y\' - 2x^{-3}y &= 4x^{-1} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (x^{-2}y) &= 4x^{-1} \\\\\n		d(x^{-2}y) &= 4x^{-1} dx \\\\\n		\\int d(x^{-2}y) &= \\int 4x^{-1} dx \\\\\n		x^{-2}y &= 4\\ln|x| + C_2 \\\\\n		y &= 4x^2\\ln|x| + C_2x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nPutting these two solutions together gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			2x - 1 + C_1e^{-2x} & 0 \\leq x \\leq 1 \\\\\n			4x^2\\ln|x| + C_2x^2 & x > 1\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3 &= y(0) \\\\\n		3 &= 2(0) - 1 + C_1e^{-2(0)} \\\\\n		3 &= -1 + C_1 \\\\\n		C_1 &= 4\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the other constant use the fact that the solution has to be continuous which means that at $x = 1$ the two pieces must evaluate to the same value:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2(1) - 1 + 4e^{-2(1)} &= 4(1)^2\\ln(1) + C_2(1)^2 \\\\\n		1 + 4e^{-2} &= C_2\n	}$\n</div>\nPutting all of this together gives the final solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			2x - 1 + 4e^{-2x} & 0 \\leq x \\leq 1 \\\\\n			4x^2\\ln|x| + (1 + 4e^{-2})x^2 & x > 1\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>'),(134,'Example_1',1,85,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6y\' - 2y = xy^4\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = -2$.','Right away it is clear that this differential equation conforms to the Bernoulli one. To begin divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6y\' - 2y &= xy^4 \\\\\n		6y\'y^{-4} - 2y^{-3} &= x\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-3} \\\\\n		u\' &= -3y^{-4}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6y\'y^{-4} - 2y^{-3} &= x \\\\\n		-2u\' - 2u &= x \\\\\n		u\' + u &= -\\frac{x}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int dx} \\\\\n		&= e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nMultiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' + u &= -\\frac{x}{2} \\\\\n		e^xu\' + e^xu &= -\\frac{x}{2}e^x \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(e^xu) &= -\\frac{x}{2}e^x \\\\\n		d(e^xu) &= -\\frac{x}{2}e^x dx \\\\\n		\\int d(e^xu) &= \\int -\\frac{x}{2}e^x \\\\\n		e^xu &= -\\frac{1}{2}e^x(x - 1) + C \\\\\n		u &= -\\frac{1}{2}(x - 1) + Ce^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-3} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ -\\frac{1}{2}(x - 1) + Ce^{-x} \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition, the constant of integration comes out to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-2 &= y(0) \\\\\n		-2 &= \\Big[ -\\frac{1}{2}((0) - 1) + Ce^{-(0)} \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		-2 &= \\Big[ \\frac{1}{2} + C \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		(-2)^{-3} &= \\frac{1}{2} + C \\\\\n		C &= -\\frac{5}{8}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\Big[ -\\frac{1}{2}(x - 1) - \\frac{5}{8}e^{-x} \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(135,'Example_2',2,85,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + \\frac{y}{x} - \\sqrt{y} = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = 0$.','Begin by rearranging to see the Bernoulli form and divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' + \\frac{y}{x} - \\sqrt{y} &= 0 \\\\\n		y\' + \\frac{1}{x}y &= \\sqrt{y} \\\\\n		y\'y^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\frac{1}{x}y^\\frac{1}{2} &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		u\' &= \\frac{1}{2}y^{-\\frac{1}{2}}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\frac{1}{x}y^\\frac{1}{2} &= 1 \\\\\n		2u\' + \\frac{1}{x}u &= 1 \\\\\n		u\' + \\frac{1}{2x}u &= \\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int \\frac{1}{2x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\frac{1}{2}\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x|^\\frac{1}{2})} \\\\\n		&= |x|^\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		&= x^\\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since putting a negative sign in front will not change anything. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' + \\frac{1}{2x}u &= \\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		x^\\frac{1}{2}u\' + \\frac{1}{2x^\\frac{1}{2}}u &= \\frac{1}{2}x^\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(x^\\frac{1}{2}u) &= \\frac{1}{2}x^\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		d(x^\\frac{1}{2}u) &= \\frac{1}{2}x^\\frac{1}{2} dx \\\\\n		\\int d(x^\\frac{1}{2}u) &= \\frac{1}{2} \\int x^\\frac{1}{2} dx \\\\\n		x^\\frac{1}{2}u &= \\frac{1}{3}x^\\frac{3}{2} + C \\\\\n		u &= \\frac{1}{3}x^\\frac{1}{2} + Cx^{-\\frac{1}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^\\frac{1}{2} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^2 \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\frac{1}{3}x^\\frac{1}{2} + Cx^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\Big]^2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition, the constant of integration comes out to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y(1) \\\\\n		0 &= \\Big[ \\frac{1}{3}(1)^\\frac{1}{2} + C(1)^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\Big]^2 \\\\\n		0 &= \\Big[ \\frac{1}{3} + C \\Big]^2 \\\\\n		C &= -\\frac{1}{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\Big[ \\frac{1}{3}x^\\frac{1}{2} - \\frac{1}{3}x^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\Big]^2\n	}$\n</div>'),(136,'Example_3',3,85,'Determine the family of solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = 5y - 5ty^3\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by rearranging to see the Bernoulli form and divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= 5y - 5ty^3 \\\\\n		y\' - 5y &= -5ty^3 \\\\\n		y\'y^{-3} - 5y^{-2} &= -5t\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-2} \\\\\n		u\' &= -2y^{-3}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-3} - 5y^{-2} &= -5t \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{2}u\' - 5u &= -5t \\\\\n		u\' + 10u &= 10t\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(t) dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int 10 dt} \\\\\n		&= e^{10t}\n	}$\n</div>\nMultiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' + 10u &= 10t \\\\\n		e^{10t}u\' + 10e^{10t}u &= 10te^{10t} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt}(e^{10t}u) &= 10te^{10t} \\\\\n		d(e^{10t}u) &= 10te^{10t} dt \\\\\n		\\int d(e^{10t}u) &= \\int 10te^{10t} dt \\\\\n		e^{10t}u &= \\frac{1}{10}e^{10t}(10t - 1) + C \\\\\n		u &= \\frac{1}{10}(10t - 1) + Ce^{-10t}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-2} &= u \\\\\n		y &= \\pm u^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\\n		&= \\pm \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{10}(10t - 1) + Ce^{-10t}}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(137,'Example_4',4,85,'Determine the family of solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\\frac{dy}{dx} + y = y^2x^2\\ln(x)\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by rearranging to see the Bernoulli form and divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\\frac{dy}{dx} + y &= y^2x^2\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{1}{x}y &= y^2x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		y\'y^{-2} + \\frac{1}{x}y^{-1} &= x\\ln(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-1} \\\\\n		u\' &= -y^{-2}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-2} + \\frac{1}{x}y^{-1} &= x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		-u\' + \\frac{1}{x}u &= x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		u\' - \\frac{1}{x}u &= -x\\ln(x)\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -\\frac{1}{x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x|^{-1})} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{|x|} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since putting a negative sign in front will not change anything. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' - \\frac{1}{x}u &= -x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{x}u\' - \\frac{1}{x^2}u &= -\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}\\Big( \\frac{u}{x} \\Big) &= -\\ln(x) \\\\\n		d\\Big( \\frac{u}{x} \\Big) &= -\\ln(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int d\\Big( \\frac{u}{x} \\Big) &= \\int -\\ln(x) dx \\\\\n		\\frac{u}{x} &= -x\\ln(x) + x + C \\\\\n		u &= -x^2\\ln(x) + x^2 + Cx\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-1} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{-x^2\\ln(x) + x^2 + Cx}\n	}$\n</div>'),(138,'Example_5',5,85,'Determine the family of solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{2}{x}y = -x^2\\cos(x)y^2\n	}$\n</div>','Right away it is clear that this differential equation conforms to the Bernoulli one. To begin divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{2}{x}y &= -x^2\\cos(x)y^2 \\\\\n		y\'y^{-2} + \\frac{2}{x}y^{-1} &= -x^2\\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-1} \\\\\n		u\' &= -y^{-2}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-2} + \\frac{2}{x}y^{-1} &= -x^2\\cos(x) \\\\\n		-u\' + \\frac{2}{x}u &= -x^2\\cos(x) \\\\\n		u\' - \\frac{2}{x}u &= x^2\\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -\\frac{2}{x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-2\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x|^{-2})} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{|x|^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since squaring guarantees a positive result. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' - \\frac{2}{x}u &= x^2\\cos(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{x^2} - \\frac{2}{x^3}u &= \\cos(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}\\Big( \\frac{u}{x^2} \\Big) &= \\cos(x) \\\\\n		d\\Big( \\frac{u}{x^2} \\Big) &= \\cos(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int d\\Big( \\frac{u}{x^2} \\Big) &= \\int \\cos(x) dx \\\\\n		\\frac{u}{x^2} &= \\sin(x) + C \\\\\n		u &= x^2\\sin(x) + Cx^2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-1} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{x^2\\sin(x) + Cx^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(139,'Example_6',6,85,'Solve the following differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\\frac{dy}{dx} + 5y = 2x^2y^4\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = 3$.','Begin by rearranging to see the Bernoulli form and divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\\frac{dy}{dx} + 5y &= 2x^2y^4 \\\\\n		y\' + \\frac{5}{x}y &= 2xy^4 \\\\\n		y\'y^{-4} + \\frac{5}{x}y^{-3} &= 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-3} \\\\\n		u\' &= -3y^{-4}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-4} + \\frac{5}{x}y^{-3} &= 2x \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{3}u\' + \\frac{5}{x}u &= 2x \\\\\n		u\' - \\frac{15}{x}u &= -6x\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -\\frac{15}{x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-15\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x|^{-15})} \\\\\n		&= |x|^{-15} \\\\\n		&= x^{-15}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since putting a negative sign in front will not change anything. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' - \\frac{15}{x}u &= -6x \\\\\n		x^{-15}u\' - 15x^{-16}u &= -6x^{-14} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(x^{-15}u) &= -6x^{-14} \\\\\n		d(x^{-15}u) &= -6x^{-14} dx \\\\\n		\\int d(x^{-15}u) &= \\int -6x^{-14} dx \\\\\n		x^{-15}u &= \\frac{6}{13}x^{-13} + C \\\\\n		u &= \\frac{6}{13}x^2 + Cx^15\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-3} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\frac{6}{13}x^2 + Cx^15 \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition, the constant of integration comes out to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3 &= y(1) \\\\\n		3 &= \\Big[ \\frac{6}{13}(1)^2 + C(1)^15 \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		(3)^{-3} &= \\frac{6}{13} + C \\\\\n		C &= -\\frac{149}{351}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the final solution can be written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\Big[ \\frac{6}{13}x^2 - \\frac{149}{351}x^15 \\Big]^{-\\frac{1}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(140,'Example_7',7,85,'Determine the family of solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = y\\cot(x) + y^3\\csc(x)\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by rearranging to see the Bernoulli form and divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= y\\cot(x) + y^3\\csc(x) \\\\\n		y\' - \\cot(x)y &= \\csc(x)y^3 \\\\\n		y\'y^{-3} - \\cot(x)y^{-2} &= \\csc(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-2} \\\\\n		u\' &= -2y^{-3}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-3} - \\cot(x)y^{-2} &= \\csc(x) \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{2}u\' - \\cot(x)u &= \\csc(x) \\\\\n		u\' + 2\\cot(x)u &= -2\\csc(x)\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int 2\\cot(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{2\\ln|\\sin(x)|} \\\\\n		&= |\\sin(x)|^2 \\\\\n		&= \\sin^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since squaring guarantees a positive result. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' + 2\\cot(x)u &= -2\\csc(x) \\\\\n		\\sin^2(x)u\' + 2\\cos(x)\\sin(x)u &= -2\\sin(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(\\sin^2(x)u) &= -2\\sin(x) \\\\\n		d(\\sin^2(x)u) &= -2\\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int d(\\sin^2(x)u) &= \\int -2\\sin(x) dx \\\\\n		\\sin^2(x)u &= 2\\cos(x) + C \\\\\n		u &= \\frac{2\\cos(x) + C}{\\sin^2(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-2} &= u \\\\\n		y &= \\pm u^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\\n		&= \\pm \\Big( \\frac{2\\cos(x) + C}{\\sin^2(x)} \\Big)^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\\n		&= \\pm \\frac{|\\sin(x)|}{\\sqrt{2\\cos(x) + C}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(141,'Example_8',8,85,'Determine the family of solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{1}{3}y = e^xy^4\n	}$\n</div>','Right away it is clear that this differential equation conforms to the Bernoulli one. To begin divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{1}{3}y &= e^xy^4 \\\\\n		y\'y^{-4} + \\frac{1}{3}y^{-3} &= e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-3} \\\\\n		u\' &= -3y^{-4}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-4} + \\frac{1}{3}y^{-3} &= e^x \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{3}u\' + \\frac{1}{3}u &= e^x \\\\\n		u\' - u &= -3e^x\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -1 dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since squaring guarantees a positive result. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' - u &= -3e^x \\\\\n		e^{-x}u\' - e^{-x}u &= -3 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(e^{-x}u) &= -3 \\\\\n		d(e^{-x}u) &= -3 dx \\\\\n		\\int d(e^{-x}u) &= \\int -3 dx \\\\\n		e^{-x}u &= -3x + C \\\\\n		u &= -3xe^x + Ce^x\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-3} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		&= \\Big( -3xe^x + Ce^x \\Big)^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n	}$\n</div>'),(142,'Example_9',9,85,'Determine the family of solutions to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{1}{x}y = y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand the interval of existance for each solution.','Right away it is clear that this differential equation conforms to the Bernoulli one. To begin divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{1}{x}y &= y^2 \\\\\n		y\'y^{-2} + \\frac{1}{x}y^{-1} &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y^{-1} \\\\\n		u\' &= -y^{-2}y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'y^{-2} + \\frac{1}{x}y^{-1} &= 1 \\\\\n		-u\' + \\frac{1}{x}u &= 1 \\\\\n		u\' - \\frac{1}{x}u &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(x) dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -\\frac{1}{x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{|x|} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since putting a negative sign in front will not change anything. Next multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' - \\frac{1}{x}u &= -1 \\\\\n		x^{-1}u\' - x^{-2}u &= -x^{-1} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx}(x^{-1}u) &= -x^{-1} \\\\\n		d(x^{-1}u) &= -x^{-1} dx \\\\\n		\\int d(x^{-1}u) &= \\int -x^{-1} dx \\\\\n		x^{-1}u &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		u &= -x\\ln|x| + Cx\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $y$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{-1} &= u \\\\\n		y &= u^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{-x\\ln|x| + Cx}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the interval of existance, we just have to account for the vertical asymptotes of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -x\\ln|x| + Cx \\\\\n		0 &= x(-\\ln|x| + C) \\\\\n		x &= 0, e^C, -e^C\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the bad points accounted for, the interval of existance for all solutions is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(-\\infty, -e^C) \\cup (-e^C, 0) \\cup (0, e^C) \\cup (e^C, \\infty)\n	}$\n</div>'),(143,'Example_10',10,85,'Solve the following differential equation for an explicit solution and determine its interval of existance:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(xy + x^2y^3)y\' = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y\\Big( -\\frac{1}{2} \\Big) = 2$.','Begin by rearranging to see the Bernoulli form and divide throughout by the non-linear term:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(xy + x^2y^3)y\' &= 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{1}{xy + x^2y^3} \\\\\n		\\frac{dx}{dy} &= xy + x^2y^3 \\\\\n		x\' - yx &= y^3x^2 \\\\\n		x\'x^{-2} - yx^{-1} &= y^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= x^{-1} \\\\\n		u\' &= -x^{-2}x\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\'x^{-2} - yx^{-1} &= y^3 \\\\\n		-u\' - yu &= y^3 \\\\\n		u\' + yu &= -y^3\n	}$\n</div>\na first order linear differential equation. Now an integrating factor is needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int p(y) dy} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int y dy} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNext multiplying throughout and solving for $u$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u\' + yu &= -y^3 \\\\\n		e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}u\' + ye^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}u &= -y^3e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dy}(e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}u) &= -y^3e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}} \\\\\n		d(e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}u) &= -y^3e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}} dy \\\\\n		\\int d(e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}u) &= \\int -y^3e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}} dy \\\\\n		e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}u &= -e^{\\frac{y^2}{2}}(y^2 - 2) + C \\\\\n		u &= -y^2 + 2 + Ce^{-\\frac{y^2}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $x$ use the original substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^{-1} &= u \\\\\n		x &= u^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{-y^2 + 2 + Ce^{-\\frac{y^2}{2}}}\n	}$\n</div>\nGiven that $y\\Big( \\frac{1}{2} \\Big) = 2$ is the same as saying that the point $\\Big( -\\frac{1}{2}, 2 \\Big)$ must lie on the curve representing the particular solution. So:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x &= \\frac{1}{-y^2 + 2 + Ce^{-\\frac{(2)^2}{2}}} \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{2} &= \\frac{1}{-(2)^2 + 2 + Ce^{-2}} \\\\\n		-2 &= -2 + Ce^{-2} \\\\\n		0 &= Ce^{-2} \\\\\n		C &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the constant determined, the particular solution takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = \\frac{1}{-y^2 + 2} \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the interval of existance, we just have to account for the vertical asymptotes of the\nfunction:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -y^2 + 2 \\\\\n		y^2 &= 2 \\\\\n		y &= \\pm \\sqrt{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the bad points accounted for, the interval of existance for the particular solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(-\\infty, -\\sqrt{2}) \\cup (-\\sqrt{2}, \\sqrt{2}) \\cup (\\sqrt{2}, \\infty)\n	}$\n</div>'),(144,'Example_1',1,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(2x - 1)dx + (3y + 7)dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= 2x - 1 \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= 3y + 7\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (2x - 1) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} (3y + 7) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int (2x - 1) dx \\\\\n		&= x^2 - x \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int (3y + 7) dx \\\\\n		&= \\frac{3}{2}y^2 + 7y\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= x^2 - x + \\frac{3}{2}y^2 + 7y\n	}$\n</div>'),(145,'Example_2',2,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Big( 1 + \\ln(x) + \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) dx &= \\Big( 1 - \\ln(x) \\Big) dy\n	}$\n</div>','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first reorganize:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Big( 1 + \\ln(x) + \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) dx + \\Big( \\ln(x) - 1 \\Big) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= 1 + \\ln(x) + \\frac{y}{x} \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= \\ln(x) - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\Big( 1 + \\ln(x) + \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} (\\ln(x) - 1) \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{x} &= \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int \\Big( 1 + \\ln(x) + \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) dx \\\\\n		&= x + x\\ln(x) - x + y\\ln(x) \\\\\n		&= x\\ln(x) + y\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int (\\ln(x) - 1) dy \\\\\n		&= y\\ln(x) - y\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= y\\ln(x) + x\\ln(x) - y\n	}$\n</div>'),(146,'Example_3',3,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(\\tan(x) - \\sin(x)\\sin(y)) dx + \\cos(x)\\cos(y) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= \\tan(x) - \\sin(x)\\sin(y) \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= \\cos(x)\\cos(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (\\tan(x) - \\sin(x)\\sin(y)) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} (\\cos(x)\\cos(y)) \\\\\n		-\\sin(x)\\cos(y) &= -\\sin(x)\\cos(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int (\\tan(x) - \\sin(x)\\sin(y)) dx \\\\\n		&= \\ln|\\sec(x)| + \\cos(x)\\sin(y) \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int (\\cos(x)\\cos(y)) dy \\\\\n		&= \\cos(x)\\sin(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\ln|\\sec(x)| + \\cos(x)\\sin(y)\n	}$\n</div>'),(147,'Example_4',4,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{3y^2 - t^2}{y^5} \\frac{dy}{dt} + \\frac{t}{2y^4} = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = 1$.','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first reorganize:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{3y^2 - t^2}{y^5} \\frac{dy}{dt} + \\frac{t}{2y^4} &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{t}{2y^4} dt + \\frac{3y^2 - t^2}{y^5} dy &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(t,y) &= \\frac{t}{2y^4} \\\\\n		N(t,y) &= \\frac{3y^2 - t^2}{y^5}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_t \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\frac{t}{2y^4} &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t} \\frac{3y^2 - t^2}{y^5} \\\\\n		-\\frac{2t}{y^5} &= -\\frac{2t}{y^5}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(t,y) dt &= \\int \\frac{t}{2y^4} dt \\\\\n		&= \\frac{t^2}{4y^4} \\\\\n		\\int N(t,y) dy &= \\int \\frac{3y^2 - t^2}{y^5} dy \\\\\n		&= \\int (3y^{-3} - t^2y^{-5}) dy \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{3}{2}y^{-2} + \\frac{1}{4}t^2y^{-4}\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\frac{t^2}{4y^4} - \\frac{3}{2y^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to satisfy the initial condition the solution must lie along the curve that passes through the point $(1,1)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\frac{t^2}{4y^4} - \\frac{3}{2y^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(1)^2}{4(1)^4} - \\frac{3}{2(1)^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{3}{2} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{5}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the final solution is written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-\\frac{5}{4} &= \\frac{t^2}{4y^4} - \\frac{3}{2y^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(148,'Example_5',5,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(y^2\\cos(x) - 3x^2y - 2x) dx + (2y\\sin(x) - x^3 + \\ln(y)) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = e$.','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= y^2\\cos(x) - 3x^2y - 2x \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= 2y\\sin(x) - x^3 + \\ln(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (y^2\\cos(x) - 3x^2y - 2x) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} (2y\\sin(x) - x^3 + \\ln(y)) \\\\\n		2y\\cos(x) - 3x^2 &= 2y\\cos(x) - 3x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int (y^2\\cos(x) - 3x^2y - 2x) dx \\\\\n		&= y^2\\sin(x) - x^3y - x^2 \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int (2y\\sin(x) - x^3 + \\ln(y)) dy \\\\\n		&= y^2\\sin(x) - x^3y + y\\ln(y) - y\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= y^2\\sin(x) - x^3y - x^2 + y\\ln(y) - y\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to satisfy the initial condition the solution must lie along the curve that passes through the point $(0,e)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= y^2\\sin(x) - x^3y - x^2 + y\\ln(y) - y \\\\\n		&= (e)^2\\sin(0) - (0)^3(e) - (0)^2 + (e)\\ln(e) - e \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the final solution is written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y^2\\sin(x) - x^3y - x^2 + y\\ln(y) - y\n	}$\n</div>'),(149,'Example_6',6,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Big( \\frac{1}{1 + y^2} + \\cos(x) - 2xy \\Big) \\frac{dy}{dx} = y(y + \\sin(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = 1$.','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first reorganize:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Big( \\frac{1}{1 + y^2} + \\cos(x) - 2xy \\Big) \\frac{dy}{dx} &= y(y + \\sin(x)) \\\\\n		-y(y + \\sin(x)) dx + \\Big( \\frac{1}{1 + y^2} + \\cos(x) - 2xy \\Big) dy &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= -y(y + \\sin(x)) \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= \\frac{1}{1 + y^2} + \\cos(x) - 2xy\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (-y(y + \\sin(x))) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} \\Big( \\frac{1}{1 + y^2} + \\cos(x) - 2xy \\Big) \\\\\n		-(y + \\sin(x)) - y &= -\\sin(x) - 2y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int -y(y + \\sin(x)) dx \\\\\n		&= -y^2x + y\\cos(x) \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int \\Big( \\frac{1}{1 + y^2} + \\cos(x) - 2xy \\Big) dy \\\\\n		&= \\arctan(y) + y\\cos(x) - xy^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= y\\cos(x) - xy^2 + \\arctan(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to satisfy the initial condition the solution must lie along the curve that passes through the point $(0,1)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= y\\cos(x) - xy^2 + \\arctan(y) \\\\\n		&= (1)\\cos(0) - (0)(1)^2 + \\arctan(1) \\\\\n		&= 1 - \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{4 - \\pi}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the final solution is written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{4 - \\pi}{4} &= y\\cos(x) - xy^2 + \\arctan(y)\n	}$\n</div>'),(150,'Example_7',7,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(2y^2 + 3x) dx + 2xy dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= 2y^2 + 3x \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= 2xy\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (2y^2 + 3x) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} (2xy) \\\\\n		4y &\\neq 2y\n	}$\n</div>\nUnfortunately the condition does not hold, but perhaps an integrating factor can fix this:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu(x) &= e^{\\int \\frac{M_y - N_x}{N} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int \\frac{4y - 2y}{2xy} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int \\frac{dx}{x}} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= |x| \\\\\n		&= x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the absolute value can be dropped since multiplying by a constant will not change the outcome. Now:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (2y^2x + 3x^2) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} (2x^2y) \\\\\n		4yx &= 4xy\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int (2y^2x + 3x^2) dx \\\\\n		&= y^2x^2 + x^3 \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int (2x^2y) dy \\\\\n		&= x^2y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= x^2y^2 + x^3\n	}$\n</div>'),(151,'Example_8',8,86,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x^2 + y^2 - 5) dx = (y + xy) dy\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = 1$.','If we are to guess that this equation is exact, first reorganize:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x^2 + y^2 - 5) dx + (-y - xy) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= x^2 + y^2 - 5 \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= -y - xy\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to check if these satisfy the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} (x^2 + y^2 - 5) &= (\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}) (-y - xy) \\\\\n		2y &\\neq -y\n	}$\n</div>\nUnfortunately the condition does not hold, but perhaps an integrating factor can fix this:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu(x) &= e^{\\int \\frac{M_y - N_x}{N} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int \\frac{(2y) - (-y)}{-y - xy} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int \\frac{3y}{y(-1 - x)} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\int -\\frac{3}{(1 + x)} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{-3\\ln|x + 1|} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\ln(|x + 1|^{-3})} \\\\\n		&= |x + 1|^{-3} \\\\\n		&= (x + 1)^{-3}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the absolute value can be dropped since multiplying by a constant will not change the outcome. Now:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} \\frac{x^2 + y^2 - 5}{(x + 1)^3} &= (\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}) -y \\cdot \\frac{1 + x}{(1 + x)^3} \\\\\n		\\frac{2y}{(x + 1)^3} &= \\frac{2y}{(x + 1)^3}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int \\frac{x^2 + y^2 - 5}{(x + 1)^3} dx \\\\\n		&= \\frac{4x + 8}{2(x + 1)^2} + \\ln|x + 1| - \\frac{y^2}{2(x + 1)^2} \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int -y \\cdot \\frac{1 + x}{(1 + x)^3} dy \\\\\n		&= -y^2 \\cdot \\frac{1}{2(1 + x)^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C = \\frac{4x + 8}{2(x + 1)^2} + \\ln|x + 1| - \\frac{y^2}{2(x + 1)^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the value of the constant using the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\frac{4x + 8}{2(x + 1)^2} + \\ln|x + 1| - \\frac{y^2}{2(x + 1)^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{4(0) + 8}{2((0) + 1)^2} + \\ln|(0) + 1| - \\frac{(1)^2}{2((0) + 1)^2} \\\\\n		&= 4 + 0 - \\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{7}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nPutting it all together, the final solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{7}{2} = \\frac{4x + 8}{2(x + 1)^2} + \\ln|x + 1| - \\frac{y^2}{2(x + 1)^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(152,'Example_9',9,86,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) dx + \\Big( xe^{xy} + 2xy + \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine $M(x,y)$ s.t. the differential equation is exact.','First identify the component as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		N(x,y) = xe^{xy} + 2xy + \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow in order for it to be exact, the condition must hold:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		M_y &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} \\Big( xe^{xy} + 2xy + \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) \\\\\n		M_y &= xye^{xy} + 2y - \\frac{1}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can determine $M(x,y)$ as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= \\int M_y dy \\\\\n		&= \\int \\Big( xye^{xy} + 2y - \\frac{1}{x^2} \\Big) dy \\\\\n		&= \\frac{e^{xy}(xy - 1)}{x} + y^2 - \\frac{y}{x^2} + f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that the solution has an extra function of $x$ only. This occurs because the condition uses the partial derivative with respect to $y$ and thus when checking that function will disappear. In general this is the final solution unless more information is given.'),(153,'Example_10',10,86,'Prove that all first order separable differential equations are exact.','Any separable differential equation can be written in the format:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = j(x)k(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow reorganizing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= j(x)k(y) \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{k(y)} dy &= j(x) dx \\\\\n		-j(x) dx + \\frac{1}{k(y)} dy &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand identifying the components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) &= -j(x) \\\\\n		N(x,y) &= \\frac{1}{k(y)}\n	}$\n</div>\nchecks the condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M_y &= N_x \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} -j(x) &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} \\frac{1}{k(y)} \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, to determine the solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\int M(x,y) dx &= \\int -j(x) dx \\\\\n		&= -J(x) \\\\\n		\\int N(x,y) dy &= \\int \\frac{1}{k(y)} dx \\\\\n		&= K(y)\n	}$\n</div>\nPutting all of this together gives the final solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C = K(y) - J(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		K(y) = \\int \\frac{dy}{k(y)} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} J(x) = \\int j(x) dx\n	}$\n</div>'),(154,'Example_1',1,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x - y) dx + x dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>','First rewriting this gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x - y) dx + x dy &= 0 \\\\\n		x dy &= (y - x) dx \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{y - x}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= \\frac{y - x}{x} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= \\frac{(ty) - (tx)}{(tx)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{y - x}{x} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{y - x}{x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{ux - x}{x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= u - 1 \\\\\n		u\'x &= -1 \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} x &= -1 \\\\\n		du &= -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int du &= \\int -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		u &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		u + \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{y}{x} + \\ln|x| = C\n	}$\n</div>\nTypically solutions are left in implicit form, but this solution can actually be written in explicit form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{y}{x} + \\ln|x| &= C \\\\\n		\\frac{y}{x} &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		y &= -x\\ln|x| + Cx\n	}$\n</div>'),(155,'Example_2',2,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\\frac{dy}{dx} = y + \\sqrt{x^2 - y^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x > 0$.','First rewriting this gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\\frac{dy}{dx} &= y + \\sqrt{x^2 - y^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{y + \\sqrt{x^2 - y^2}}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= \\frac{y + \\sqrt{x^2 - y^2}}{x} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= \\frac{(ty) + \\sqrt{(tx)^2 - (ty)^2}}{(tx)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{ty + t\\sqrt{x^2 - y^2}}{tx} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{y + \\sqrt{x^2 - y^2}}{x} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{y + \\sqrt{x^2 - y^2}}{x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{ux + \\sqrt{x^2 - u^2x^2}}{x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= u + \\sqrt{1 - u^2} \\\\\n		u\'x &= \\sqrt{1 - u^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} x &= \\sqrt{1 - u^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{\\sqrt{1 - u^2}} &= \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{du}{\\sqrt{1 - u^2}} &= \\int \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\arcsin(u) &= \\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\arcsin(u) - \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\arcsin\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) - \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>'),(156,'Example_3',3,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{x + 3y}{3x + y}\n	}$\n</div>','To see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= \\frac{x + 3y}{3x + y} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= \\frac{(tx) + 3(ty)}{3(tx) + (ty)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{x + 3y}{3x + y} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{x + 3y}{3x + y} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{x + 3(ux)}{3x + (ux)} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{1 + 3u}{3 + u} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= \\frac{1 + 3u}{3 + u} - \\frac{u(3 + u)}{3 + u} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= \\frac{1 - u^2}{3 + u} \\\\\n		\\frac{3 + u}{1 - u^2} du &= \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{3 + u}{1 - u^2} du &= \\int \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\ln|1 + u| - 2\\ln|1 - u| &= \\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\ln\\Bigg| \\frac{1 + u}{(1 - u)^2} \\Bigg| - \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln\\Bigg| \\frac{1 + \\frac{y}{x}}{(1 - \\frac{y}{x})^2} \\Bigg| - \\ln|x| &= C \\\\\n		\\ln\\Bigg| \\frac{x^2 + xy}{(x - y)^2} \\Bigg| - \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>'),(157,'Example_4',4,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-y dx + (x + \\sqrt{xy}) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>','First rewriting this gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-y dx + (x + \\sqrt{xy}) dy &= 0 \\\\\n		(x + \\sqrt{xy}) dy &= y dx \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{y}{x + \\sqrt{xy}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= \\frac{y}{x + \\sqrt{xy}} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= \\frac{(ty)}{(tx) + \\sqrt{(tx)(ty)}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{y}{x + \\sqrt{xy}} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{y}{x + \\sqrt{xy}} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{ux}{x + \\sqrt{ux^2}} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{u}{1 + \\sqrt{u}} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= \\frac{u}{1 + \\sqrt{u}} - \\frac{u(1 + \\sqrt{u})}{1 + \\sqrt{u}} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= -\\frac{u^{\\frac{3}{2}}}{1 + \\sqrt{u}} \\\\\n		\\frac{1 + \\sqrt{u}}{u^{\\frac{3}{2}}} du &= -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{1 + \\sqrt{u}}{u^{\\frac{3}{2}}} du &= \\int -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		-2u^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + \\ln|u| &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\ln|ux| - \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{u}} &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln|y| - \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{\\frac{y}{x}}} = C\n	}$\n</div>'),(158,'Example_5',5,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{y - x}{y + x}\n	}$\n</div>','To see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= \\frac{y - x}{y + x} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= \\frac{(ty) - (tx)}{(ty) + (tx)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{y - x}{y + x} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{y - x}{y + x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{(ux) - x}{(ux) + x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{u - 1}{u + 1} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= \\frac{u - 1}{u + 1} - \\frac{u(u + 1)}{u + 1} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= -\\frac{u^2 + 1}{u + 1} \\\\\n		\\frac{u + 1}{u^2 + 1} du &= -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{u + 1}{u^2 + 1} du &= \\int -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}\\ln|u^2 + 1| + \\arctan(u) &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}\\ln|u^2 + 1| + \\arctan(u) + \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{1}{2}\\ln\\Bigg| \\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big)^2 + 1 \\Bigg| + \\arctan\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) + \\ln|x| = C\n	}$\n</div>'),(159,'Example_6',6,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x^2 + 2y^2)\\frac{dy}{dx} = xy\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(-1) = 1$.','First rewriting this gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x^2 + 2y^2)\\frac{dy}{dx} &= xy \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= \\frac{xy}{x^2 + 2y^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= \\frac{xy}{x^2 + 2y^2} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= \\frac{(tx)(ty)}{(tx)^2 + 2(ty)^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{xy}{x^2 + 2y^2} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{xy}{x^2 + 2y^2} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{x(ux)}{x^2 + 2(ux)^2} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{u}{1 + 2u^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= \\frac{u}{1 + 2u^2} - \\frac{u(1 + 2u^2)}{1 + 2u^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= -\\frac{2u^3}{1 + 2u^2} \\\\\n		\\frac{1 + 2u^2}{2u^3} du &= -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{1 + 2u^2}{2u^3} du &= \\int -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{4}u^{-2} + \\ln|u| &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{4u^2} + \\ln|ux| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-\\frac{x^2}{4y^2} + \\ln|y| = C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= -\\frac{x^2}{4y^2} + \\ln|y| \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{(-1)^2}{4(1)^2} + \\ln|(1)| \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{1}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nthe final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-\\frac{x^2}{4y^2} + \\ln|y| = -\\frac{1}{4}\n	}$\n</div>'),(160,'Example_7',7,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y dx + x(\\ln(x) - \\ln(y) - 1) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = e$.','First rewriting this gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y dx + x(\\ln(x) - \\ln(y) - 1) dy &= 0 \\\\\n		x(\\ln(x) - \\ln(y) - 1) dy &= -y dx \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -\\frac{y}{x(\\ln(xy^{-1}) - 1)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= -\\frac{y}{x(\\ln(xy^{-1}) - 1)} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= -\\frac{(ty)}{(tx)(\\ln((tx)(ty)^{-1}) - 1)} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{y}{x(\\ln(xy^{-1}) - 1)} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= -\\frac{y}{x(\\ln(xy^{-1}) - 1)} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= -\\frac{ux}{x(\\ln(x(ux)^{-1}) - 1)} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= \\frac{u}{\\ln(u) + 1} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= \\frac{u}{\\ln(u) + 1} - \\frac{u(\\ln(u) + 1)}{\\ln(u) + 1} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= -\\frac{u\\ln(u)}{\\ln(u) + 1} \\\\\n		\\frac{\\ln(u) + 1}{u\\ln(u)} du &= -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{\\ln(u) + 1}{u\\ln(u)} du &= \\int -\\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\ln|u| + \\ln|\\ln(u)| &= -\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\ln|ux| + \\ln|\\ln(u)| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln|y| + \\ln\\Bigg| \\ln\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) \\Bigg| = C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\ln|y| + \\ln\\Bigg| \\ln\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) \\Bigg| \\\\\n		&= \\ln(e) + \\ln\\Bigg| \\ln\\Big( \\frac{(e)}{(1)} \\Big) \\Bigg| \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nthe final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln|y| + \\ln\\Bigg| \\ln\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big) \\Bigg| = 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(161,'Example_8',8,87,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x + ye^{\\frac{y}{x}}) dx - xe^{\\frac{y}{x}} dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(1) = 0$.','First rewriting this gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x + ye^{\\frac{y}{x}}) dx - xe^{\\frac{y}{x}} dy &= 0 \\\\\n		xe^{\\frac{y}{x}} dy &= (x + ye^{\\frac{y}{x}}) dx \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= e^{-\\frac{y}{x}} + \\frac{y}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to see if the homogeneous substitution can be used, first lets check that the function is homogeneous with degree zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= e^{-\\frac{y}{x}} + \\frac{y}{x} \\\\\n		f(tx,ty) &= e^{-\\frac{(ty)}{(tx)}} + \\frac{(ty)}{(tx)} \\\\\n		&= e^{-\\frac{y}{x}} + \\frac{y}{x} \\\\\n		&= f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith the condition checked, using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= ux \\\\\n		y\' &= u\'x + u\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= e^{-\\frac{y}{x}} + \\frac{y}{x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= e^{-\\frac{ux}{x}} + \\frac{ux}{x} \\\\\n		u\'x + u &= e^{-u} + u \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= e^{-u} \\\\\n		e^u du &= \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int e^u du &= \\int \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		e^u &= \\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		e^u - \\ln|x| &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish off consider that the original equation started with $x$\'s and $y$\'s, but so far we have a solution in terms of $x$\'s and $u$\'s. So replace all of the $u$\'s to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\frac{y}{x}} - \\ln|x| = C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= e^{\\frac{y}{x}} - \\ln|x| \\\\\n		&= e^{\\frac{0}{1}} - \\ln(1) \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nthe final solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\frac{y}{x}} - \\ln|x| = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nIn this scenario it is even possible to get the solution in explicit form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\frac{y}{x}} - \\ln|x| &= 1 \\\\\n		e^{\\frac{y}{x}} &= \\ln|x| + 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{y}{x} &= \\ln(\\ln|x| + 1) \\\\\n		y &= x\\ln(\\ln|x| + 1)\n	}$\n</div>'),(162,'Example_9',9,87,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M(x,y) dx + N(x,y) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nProve that a homogeneous substitution can be used iff $M(x,y)$ and $N(x,y)$ are both homogeneous of the same degree.','Proving iff statements requires showing both directions. First reorganizing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = -\\frac{M(x,y)}{N(x,y)}\n	}$\n</div>\nand assuming that the function is homogeneous, it must satisfy:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) &= f(tx,ty) \\\\\n		-\\frac{M(x,y)}{N(x,y)} &= -\\frac{M(tx,ty)}{N(tx,ty)} \\\\\n		-\\frac{M(x,y)}{N(x,y)} &= -\\frac{t^\\alpha M(x,y)}{t^\\beta N(x,y)}\n	}$\n</div>\nI have pulled out the $t$\'s at the last step since it is the only chance to make the statement true since all the $t$\'s must cancel. For this very same reasoning we must have it s.t. $\\alpha = \\beta$, which states the both components are homogeneous of the same degree. Now assuming that both functions are homogeneous of the same degree looking above it should be clear right away that the general function is going to be homogeneous of degree zero.'),(163,'Example_10',10,87,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(a_0x + a_1y + a_2) dx + (b_0x + b_1y + b_2) dy = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand the transformation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		t &= x + \\alpha \\\\\n		z &= y + \\beta\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\alpha, \\beta \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ in terms of the $a$\'s and $b$\'s s.t. the differential equation can be solved using a homogeneous substitution. You may assume that $a_0b_1 - a_1b_0 \\neq 0$ in order to write down a unique solution.','First reorganizing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = -\\frac{a_0x + a_1y + a_2}{b_0x + b_1y + b_2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		t &= x + \\alpha \\implies dt = dx \\\\\n		z &= y + \\beta \\implies dz = dy\n	}$\n</div>\nand with this the differential equation can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -\\frac{a_0x + a_1y + a_2}{b_0x + b_1y + b_2} \\\\\n		\\frac{dz}{dt} &= -\\frac{a_0(t - \\alpha) + a_1(z - \\beta) + a_2}{b_0(t - \\alpha) + b_1(z - \\beta) + b_2} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{a_0t + a_1z + (a_2 - a_0\\alpha - a_1\\beta)}{b_0t + b_1z + (b_2 - b_0\\alpha - b_1\\beta)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for this function to be homogeneous of degree zero we must have the constants on both the numerator and denominator disappear:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_2 - a_0\\alpha - a_1\\beta &= 0 \\\\\n		b_2 - b_0\\alpha - b_1\\beta &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nTo solve this system of equations for $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ first rewrite in matrix form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			a_0 & a_1 \\\\\n			b_0 & b_1\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\alpha \\\\\n			\\beta\n		\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}\n			a_2 \\\\ b_2\n		\\end{pmatrix}\n	}$\n</div>\nand use the inverse to solve the system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\alpha \\\\\n			\\beta\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\frac{1}{a_0b_1 - a_1b_0} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			b_1 & -a_1 \\\\\n			-b_0 & a_0\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			a_2 \\\\ b_2\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\frac{b_1b_2 - a_1a_2}{a_0b_1 - a_1b_0} \\\\\n			\\frac{a_0a_2 - b_0b_2}{a_0b_1 - a_1b_0}\n		\\end{pmatrix}\n	}$\n</div>'),(164,'Example_1',1,88,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x + 3y + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand the initial condition $y(1) = 5$, determine $y(1.2)$ using a $h = 0.1$ with Euler\'s Method up to four decimal places and compare the result to the exact solution by finding the error.','Using Euler\'s Method:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$n$</td>\n		    <td>$x_{n + 1} = x_n + h$</td>\n		    <td>$y_{n + 1} = y_n + hf(x_n,y_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>0</td>\n		    <td>$x_1 = x_0 + h = 1.1$</td>\n		    <td>$y_1 = y_0 + hf(x_0,y_0) = 6.8$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>1</td>\n		    <td>$x_2 = x_1 + h = 1.2$</td>\n		    <td>$y_2 = y_1 + hf(x_1,y_1) = 9.16$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nSo according to Euler\'s Method $y(1.2) \\approx 9.16$. To solve for exactly, use the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= 2x + 3y + 1 \\\\\n		u\' &= 2 + 3y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nto make the equation separable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= 2x + 3y + 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{3}(u\' - 2) &= u \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= 3u + 2 \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{3u + 2} &= dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{du}{3u + 2} &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{3}\\ln|3u + 2| &= x + C \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{3}\\ln|6x + 9y + 5| - x &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\frac{1}{3}\\ln|6x + 9y + 5| - x \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{3}\\ln|6(1) + 9(5) + 5| - 1 \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{3}\\ln(56) - 1\n	}$\n</div>\ngives the final solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{1}{3}\\ln|6x + 9y + 5| - x = \\frac{1}{3}\\ln(56) - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nTo determine the value of $y$ first lets isolate it:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{1}{3}\\ln|6x + 9y + 5| - x &= \\frac{1}{3}\\ln(56) - 1 \\\\\n		\\ln|6x + 9y + 5| &= \\ln(56) - 3 + 3x \\\\\n		6x + 9y + 5 &= e^{\\ln(56) - 3 + 3x} \\\\\n		9y &= 56e^{3x - 3} - 6x - 5 \\\\\n		y &= \\frac{56}{9}e^{3x - 3} - \\frac{2}{3}x - \\frac{5}{9}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the exact value:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(1.2) &= \\frac{56}{9}e^{3(1.2) - 3} - \\frac{2}{3}(1.2) - \\frac{5}{9}\n		&= 9.9821\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the error is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Delta = \\Big| \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{Exact} \\hspace{.1cm} - \\text{Approximation} \\hspace{.1cm} \\Big| = |9.9821 - 9.16| =  0.8221\n	}$\n</div>'),(165,'Example_2',2,88,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = 2xy\n	}$\n</div>\nand the initial condition $y(1) = 1$, determine $y(1.3)$ using a $h = 0.05$ with Euler\'s Method up to four decimal places and compare the result to the exact solution by finding the error.','Using Euler\'s Method:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$n$</td>\n		    <td>$x_{n + 1} = x_n + h$</td>\n		    <td>$y_{n + 1} = y_n + hf(x_n,y_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>0</td>\n		    <td>$x_1 = x_0 + h = 1.05$</td>\n		    <td>$y_1 = y_0 + hf(x_0,y_0) = 1.1000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		