(175,'Example_2',2,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\tan^2(x + y)\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= x + y \\\\\n		u\' &= 1 + y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\tan^2(x + y) \\\\\n		u\' - 1 &= \\tan^2(u) \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= \\tan^2(u) + 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{\\tan^2(u) + 1} &= dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{du}{\\tan^2(u) + 1} &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}(u + \\sin(u)\\cos(u)) &= x + C \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}(u + \\sin(u)\\cos(u)) - x &= C \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}(y - x + \\sin(x + y)\\cos(x + y)) &= C\n	}$\n</div>'),(176,'Example_3',3,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = 2 + \\sqrt{y - 2x + 3}\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y - 2x + 3 \\\\\n		u\' &= y\' - 2\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= 2 + \\sqrt{y - 2x + 3} \\\\\n		y\' - 2 &= \\sqrt{y - 2x + 3} \\\\\n		u\' &= \\sqrt{u} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= u^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\\n		u^{-\\frac{1}{2}} du &= dx \\\\\n		\\int u^{-\\frac{1}{2}} du &= \\int dx \\\\\n		2\\sqrt{u} &= x + C \\\\\n		2\\sqrt{y - 2x + 3} - x &= C\n	}$\n</div>'),(177,'Example_4',4,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{1 - x - y}{x + y}\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= x + y \\\\\n		u\' &= 1 + y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{1 - x - y}{x + y} \\\\\n		u\' - 1 &= \\frac{1 - u}{u} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= \\frac{1 - u}{u} + \\frac{u}{u} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= \\frac{1}{u} \\\\\n		u du &= dx \\\\\n		\\int u du &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}u^2 &= x + C \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}(x + y)^2 - x &= C\n	}$\n</div>'),(178,'Example_5',5,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = 1 + e^{y - x + 5}\n	}$\n</div>','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= y - x + 5 \\\\\n		u\' &= y\' - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= 1 + e^{y - x + 5} \\\\\n		y\' - 1 &= e^{y - x + 5} \\\\\n		u\' &= e^u \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= e^u \\\\\n		e^{-u} du &= dx \\\\\n		\\int e^{-u} du &= \\int dx \\\\\n		-e^u &= x + C \\\\\n		e^{y - x + 5} + x &= K\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		K = -C\n	}$\n</div>\ngets rid of the unnecessary negative sign.'),(179,'Example_6',6,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{3x + 2y}{3x + 2y + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(-1) = -1$.','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= 3x + 2y \\\\\n		u\' &= 3 + 2y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{3x + 2y}{3x + 2y + 2} \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}(u\' - 3) &= \\frac{u}{u + 2} \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}u\' &= \\frac{u}{u + 2} + \\frac{3(u + 2)}{u + 2} \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= \\frac{8u + 12}{u + 2} \\\\\n		\\frac{u + 2}{8u + 12} du &= dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{u + 2}{8u + 12} du &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\frac{u}{8} + \\frac{1}{16}\\ln|2u + 3| + \\frac{3}{16} &= x + C \\\\\n		\\frac{3x + 2y}{8} + \\frac{1}{16}\\ln|6x + 4y + 3| + \\frac{3}{16} - x &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the constant use the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\frac{3x + 2y}{8} + \\frac{1}{16}\\ln|6x + 4y + 3| + \\frac{3}{16} - x \\\\\n		&= \\frac{3(-1) + 2(-1)}{8} + \\frac{1}{16}\\ln|6(-1) + 4(-1) + 3| + \\frac{3}{16} - (-1) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{16}(9 + \\ln(7))\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the final solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{3x + 2y}{8} + \\frac{1}{16}\\ln|6x + 4y + 3| + \\frac{3}{16} - x = \\frac{1}{16}(9 + \\ln(7))\n	}$\n</div>'),(180,'Example_7',7,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = e^{9y - x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = 0$.','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= 9y - x \\\\\n		u\' &= 9y\' - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= e^{9y - x} \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{9}(u\' + 1) &= e^u \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= 9e^u - 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{9e^u - 1} &= dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{du}{9e^u - 1} &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{e^{-u}}{9 - e^{-u}} &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\ln|9 - e^{-u}| &= x + C \\\\\n		\\ln|9 - e^{9y - x}| - x &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the constant use the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\ln|9 - e^{9y - x}| - x \\\\\n		&= \\ln|9 - e^{9(0) - (0)}| - (0) \\\\\n		&= \\ln(8)\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the final solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln|9 - e^{9y - x}| - x = \\ln(8)\n	}$\n</div>'),(181,'Example_8',8,90,'Solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\cos(x + y) - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(0) = \\frac{\\pi}{4}$.','Since the function contains a linear input make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= x + y \\\\\n		u\' &= 1 + y\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\cos(x + y) - 1 \\\\\n		y\' + 1 &= \\cos(x + y) \\\\\n		u\' &= \\cos(u) \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx} &= \\cos(u) \\\\\n		\\sec(u) du &= dx \\\\\n		\\int \\sec(u) du &= \\int dx \\\\\n		\\ln|\\sec(u) + \\tan(u)| &= x + C \\\\\n		\\ln|\\sec(x + y) + \\tan(x + y)| - x &= C\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the constant use the initial condition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\ln|\\sec(x + y) + \\tan(x + y)| - x \\\\\n		&= \\ln\\Bigg| \\sec\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) + \\tan\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) \\Bigg| \\\\\n		&= \\ln(\\sqrt{2} + 1)\n	}$\n</div>\nand so the final solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln|\\sec(x + y) + \\tan(x + y)| - x = \\ln(\\sqrt{2} + 1)\n	}$\n</div>'),(182,'Example_9',9,90,'Keeping substitution in mind, solve the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		xy\' = y\\ln(xy)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y\'$ is the first derivative.','To motivate the approach consider the fact that we want to simplify the inside of the logarithm as much as possible. Therefore, it would be useful if the inside could become a single variable. Using the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\frac{u}{x} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{u\'x - u}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		xy\' &= y\\ln(xy) \\\\\n		x \\cdot \\frac{u\'x - u}{x^2} &= \\frac{u}{x}\\ln\\Big( x \\cdot \\frac{u}{x} \\Big) \\\\\n		u\'x - u &= u\\ln(u) \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{dx}x &= u(\\ln(u) - 1) \\\\\n		\\frac{du}{u(\\ln(u) - 1)} &= \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{du}{u(\\ln(u) - 1)} &= \\int \\frac{dx}{x} \\\\\n		\\ln|\\ln(u) - 1| &= \\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		\\ln\\Bigg| \\frac{\\ln(xy) - 1}{x} \\Bigg| &= C\n	}$\n</div>'),(183,'Example_10',10,90,'Keeping substitution in mind, rewrite the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)e^y + g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nas a first order linear differential equation.','Lets try the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= e^y \\\\\n		u\' &= uy\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= f(x)e^y + g(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{u\'}{u} &= f(x)u + g(x) \\\\\n		u\' &= f(x)u^2 + g(x)u \\\\\n		u\' - g(x)u &= f(x)u^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich unfortunately is a Bernoulli differential equation. Even though another substitution can be used to transform the Bernoulli equation into a first order linear one, instead try the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= e^{-y} \\\\\n		u\' &= -uy\'\n	}$\n</div>\non the original equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= f(x)e^y + g(x) \\\\\n		-\\frac{u\'}{u} &= f(x)u^{-1} + g(x) \\\\\n		-u\' &= f(x) + g(x)u \\\\\n		u\' + g(x)u &= -f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich gives a first order linear differential equation.'),(184,'Example_1',1,91,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = 2y\'\' + 8y\' + 6y\n	}$\n</div>\nand two independent solutions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = e^{-3x} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = e^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution and show that it satisfies the differential equation.','Since this is a homogeneous linear second order differential equation, the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo confirm this:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2y_h\'\' + 8y_h\' + 6y_h \\\\\n		0 &= 2\\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x}) + 8\\frac{d}{dx}(c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x}) + 6(c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x}) \\\\\n		0 &= 2(9c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x}) + 8(-3c_1e^{-3x} - c_2e^{-x}) + 6(c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x}) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(185,'Example_2',2,91,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = 2y\'\' + 8y\' + 6y\n	}$\n</div>\nand two independent solutions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = e^{-3x} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = e^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\nto the homogeneous differential equation and a non-homogeneous solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{\\sin(x)}{10} - \\frac{\\cos(x)}{5}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution and show that it satisfies the differential equation.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear second order differential equation, the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = y_h(x) + y_{nh}(x) = c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x} + \\frac{\\sin(x)}{10} - \\frac{\\cos(x)}{5}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo confirm this:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) &= y\'\' + 4y\' + 3y \\\\\n		\\sin(x) &= \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(y_h + y_{nh}) + 4\\frac{d}{dx}(y_h + y_{nh}) + 3(y_h + y_{nh}) \\\\\n		\\sin(x) &= \\Bigg( 9c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x} -\\frac{\\sin(x)}{10} + \\frac{\\cos(x)}{5} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 4\\Bigg( -3c_1e^{-3x} - c_2e^{-x} + \\frac{\\cos(x)}{10} + \\frac{\\sin(x)}{5} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3\\Bigg( c_1e^{-3x} + c_2e^{-x} + \\frac{\\sin(x)}{10} - \\frac{\\cos(x)}{5} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		\\sin(x) &= \\sin(x) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(186,'Example_3',3,91,'Given the differential equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 6y\' + 5y &= -9e^{2x} \\\\\n		w\'\' - 6w\' + 5w &= 5x^2 + 3x - 16\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the general solutions are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + 3e^{2x} \\\\\n		w(x) &= c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + x^2 + 3x\n	}$\n</div>\nFirst verify that these solutions indeed satisfy the differential equations and use this information to determine the solution to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		z\'\' - 6z\' + 5z &= -9e^{2x} + 5x^2 + 3x - 16\n	}$\n</div>','To verify the first solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-9e^{2x} &= y\'\' - 6y\' + 5y \\\\\n		-9e^{2x} &= \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + 3e^{2x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 6\\frac{d}{dx}(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + 3e^{2x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 5(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + 3e^{2x}) \\\\\n		-9e^{2x} &= (c_1e^x + 25c_2e^{5x} + 12e^{2x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 6(c_1e^x + 5c_2e^{5x} + 6e^{2x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 5(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + 3e^{2x}) \\\\\n		-9e^{2x} &= -9e^{2x} \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the second solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		5x^2 + 3x - 16 &= w\'\' - 6w\' + 5w \\\\\n		5x^2 + 3x - 16 &= \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + x^2 + 3x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 6\\frac{d}{dx}(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + x^2 + 3x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 5(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + x^2 + 3x) \\\\\n		5x^2 + 3x - 16 &= (c_1e^x + 25c_2e^{5x} + 2) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 6(c_1e^x + 5c_2e^{5x} + 2x + 3) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 5(c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + x^2 + 3x) \\\\\n		5x^2 + 3x - 16 &= 5x^2 + 3x - 16 \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nLastly to solve the new differential equation, using the principle of superposition of non-homogeneous differential equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		z(x) = c_1e^x + c_2e^{5x} + 3e^{2x} + x^2 + 3x\n	}$\n</div>'),(187,'Example_4',4,91,'Given the differential equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 7y\' + 12y &= x^2 \\\\\n		w\'\' + 7w\' + 12w &= e^{7x} \\\\\n		r\'\' + 7r\' + 12r &= \\cos(2x) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the general solutions are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{x^2}{12} - \\frac{7x}{72} + \\frac{37}{864} \\\\\n		w(x) &= c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{e^{7x}}{110} \\\\\n		r(x) &= c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{7\\sin(2x)}{130} + \\frac{2\\cos(2x)}{65} \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nFirst verify that these solutions indeed satisfy the differential equations and use this information to determine the solution to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		z\'\' + 7z\' + 12z &= x^2 + e^{7x} + \\cos(2x)\n	}$\n</div>','To verify the first solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 &= y\'\' + 7y\' + 12y \\\\\n		x^2 &= \\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{x^2}{12} - \\frac{7x}{72} + \\frac{37}{864} \\Big)\'\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 7\\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{x^2}{12} - \\frac{7x}{72} + \\frac{37}{864} \\Big)\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 12\\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{x^2}{12} - \\frac{7x}{72} + \\frac{37}{864} \\Big) \\\\\n		x^2 &= \\Big( 16c_1e^{-4x} + 9c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{1}{6} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big( -28c_1e^{-4x} - 21c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{7x}{6} - \\frac{49}{72} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big( 12c_1e^{-4x} + 12c_2e^{-3x} + x^2 - \\frac{7x}{6} + \\frac{37}{72} \\Big) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the second solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{7x} &= y\'\' + 7y\' + 12y \\\\\n		e^{7x} &= \\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{e^{7x}}{110} \\Big)\'\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 7\\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{e^{7x}}{110} \\Big)\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 12\\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{e^{7x}}{110} \\Big) \\\\\n		e^{7x} &= \\Big( 16c_1e^{-4x} + 9c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{49e^{7x}}{110} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big( -28c_1e^{-4x} - 21c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{49e^{7x}}{110} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big( 12c_1e^{-4x} + 12c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{12e^{7x}}{110} \\Big) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand the third solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\cos(2x) &= y\'\' + 7y\' + 12y \\\\\n		\\cos(2x) &= \\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{7\\sin(2x)}{130} + \\frac{2\\cos(2x)}{65} \\Big)\'\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 7\\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{7\\sin(2x)}{130} + \\frac{2\\cos(2x)}{65} \\Big)\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 12\\Big( c_1e^{-4x} + c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{7\\sin(2x)}{130} + \\frac{2\\cos(2x)}{65} \\Big) \\\\\n		\\cos(2x) &= \\Big( 16c_1e^{-4x} + 9c_2e^{-3x} - \\frac{28\\sin(2x)}{130} - \\frac{8\\cos(2x)}{65} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big( -28c_1e^{-4x} - 21c_2e^{-3x} + \\frac{98\\cos(2x)}{130} - \\frac{28\\sin(2x)}{65} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big( 12