ation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4y\'\' - 4y\' + y = 0\n	}$\n</div>','First we have to check for the independence of the functions by looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1, y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			e^{\\frac{x}{2}} & xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\\n			\\frac{1}{2}e^{\\frac{x}{2}} & e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + \\frac{x}{2}e^{\\frac{x}{2}}\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\Big( e^x + \\frac{x}{2}e^x \\Big) - \\Big( \\frac{x}{2}e^x \\Big) \\\\\n		&= e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nWith their independence assured, we form the homogeneous solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h = c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand check that it satisfies the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 4y_h\'\' - 4y_h\' + y_h \\\\\n		0 &= 4\\Big( c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\Big)\'\' - 4\\Big( c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\Big)\' + \\Big( c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\Big) \\\\\n		0 &= c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + 4c_2e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} - 2c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} - 4c_2e^{\\frac{x}{2}} - 2c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_1e^{\\frac{x}{2}} + c_2xe^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(190,'Example_7',7,91,'Given the set of functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ \\cos(\\ln(x)), \\sin(\\ln(x)) \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine whether $\\mathcal{S}$ satisfies as a fundamental set for the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2y\'\' + xy\' + y = 0\n	}$\n</div>','First we have to check for the independence of the functions by looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1, y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\cos(\\ln(x)) & \\sin(\\ln(x)) \\\\\n			-\\frac{\\sin(\\ln(x))