nf_n(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_1,a_2,a_3,\\dots,a_n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','A good idea might be to try a sum of multiples of the original non-homogeneous solutions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w_{nh} = a_1j_1 + a_2j_2 + a_3j_3 + \\dots + a_nj_n = \\sum_{l = 1}^n a_lj_l\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sum_{i = 1}^n a_if_i(x) &= w_{nh}\'\' + k_1w_{nh}\' + k_2w_{nh} \\\\\n		\\sum_{i = 1}^n a_if_i(x) &= \\sum_{l = 1}^n a_lj_l\'\' + k_1\\sum_{l = 1}^n a_lj_l\' + k_2\\sum_{l = 1}^n a_lj_l \\\\\n		\\sum_{i = 1}^n a_if_i(x) &= \\sum_{l = 1}^n a_l(j_l\'\' + k_1j_l\' + k_2j_l) \\\\\n		\\sum_{i = 1}^n a_if_i(x) &= \\sum_{l = 1}^n a_lf_l(x) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(194,'Example_1',1,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = \\sin(x) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine whether they are linearly independent or not.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\sin(x) & \\cos(x) \\\\\n			\\cos(x) & -\\sin(x) \n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= -\\sin^2(x) - \\cos^2(x) \\\\\n		&= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the Wronskian is non-zero, the two functions are linearly independent.'),(195,'Example_2',2,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = x^7 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = 6x^7 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x \\neq 0$, determine whether they are linearly independent or not.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			x^7 & 6x^7 + 4 \\\\\n			7x^6 & 42x^6 \n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= 42x^{13} - 42x^{13} + 28x^6 \\\\\n		&= 28x^6\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the Wronskian is non-zero, the two functions are linearly independent.'),(196,'Example_3',3,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = x^{2n} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = x^{2n-2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x \\neq 0$ and $n \\in \\mathbb{R}$, determine whether they are linearly independent or not.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			x^{2n} & x^{2n-2} \\\\\n			2nx^{2n-1} & (2n-2)x^{2n-3} \n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= (2n-2)x^{4n-3} - 2nx^{4n-3} \\\\\n		&= -2x^{4n-3}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the Wronskian is non-zero, the two functions are linearly independent.'),(197,'Example_4',4,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = \\tan(x) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = \\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine what values of $x$ make them dependent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\tan(x) & \\sin(x) \\\\\n			\\sec^2(x) & \\cos(x)\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\tan(x)\\cos(x) - \\sin(x)\\sec^2(x) \\\\\n		&= \\sin(x)(1 - \\sec^2(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nTo make them dependent we want:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		x &= n\\pi\n	}$\n</div>\nor:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sec^2(x) - 1 &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{\\cos^2(x)} &= 1 \\\\\n		\\cos^2(x) &= 1 \\\\\n		\\cos(x) &= \\pm 1 \\\\\n		x &= n\\pi\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}$.'),(198,'Example_5',5,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = e^{k_1x} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = e^{k_2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $k_1,k_2 \\in \\mathbb{R}$, determine what values of $k_1$ and $k_2$ make these two linearly dependent and independent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			e^{k_1x} & e^{k_2x} \\\\\n			k_1e^{k_1x} & k_2e^{k_2x} \n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= k_2e^{(k_1 + k_2)x} - k_1e^{(k_1 + k_2)x} \\\\\n		&= (k_2 - k_1)e^{(k_1 + k_2)x}\n	}$\n</div>\nIt seems that whenever $k_1 = k_2$ the two are linearly dependent, otherwise they are independent.'),(199,'Example_6',6,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = f(k_1x) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = f(k_2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x) \\in C^1$ and $k_1,k_2 \\in \\mathbb{R}$, determine what values of $k_1$ and $k_2$ make these two linearly dependent and independent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			f(k_1x) & f(k_2x) \\\\\n			k_1f\'(k_1x) & k_2f\'(k_2x) \n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= k_2f(k_1x)f\'(k_2x) - k_1f\'(k_1x)f(k_2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nIt seems that whenever $k_1 = k_2$ the two are linearly dependent, otherwise they are independent. This essentially states that given any function, a linearly independent function could be constructed from the one given by performing a horizontal stretch.'),(200,'Example_7',7,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = f(x) + g(x) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = f(x) - g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x),g(x) \\in C^1$, determine what condition makes the two linearly dependent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			f(x) + g(x) & f(x) - g(x) \\\\\n			f\'(x) + g\'(x) & f\'(x) - g\'(x)\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= (f(x) + g(x))(f\'(x) - g\'(x)) - (f(x) - g(x))(f\'(x) + g\'(x)) \\\\\n		&= 2(g(x)f\'(x) - f(x)g\'(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom this it seems that in order to make the two functions linearly dependent, they must satisfy:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = g(x)f\'(x) - f(x)g\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(201,'Example_8',8,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = f(x + k_1) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = f(x + k_2)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x) \\in C^1$ and $k_1,k_2 \\in \\mathbb{R}$, determine what condition makes the two linearly dependent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			f(x + k_1) & f(x + k_2) \\\\\n			f\'(x + k_1) & f\'(x + k_2)\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= f(x + k_1)f\'(x + k_2) - f(x + k_2)f\'(x + k_1)\n	}$\n</div>\nIt seems that whenever $k_1 = k_2$ the two are linearly dependent. This essentially states that given any function, a linearly independent function could be constructed from the one given by performing a horizontal translation.'),(202,'Example_9',9,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = f(x) + k_1 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = f(x) + k_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x) \\in C^1$ and $k_1,k_2 \\in \\mathbb{R}$, determine what condition makes the two linearly dependent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			f(x) + k_1 & f(x) + k_2 \\\\\n			f\'(x) & f\'(x)\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= f\'(x)(f(x) + k_1) - f\'(x)(f(x) + k_2) \\\\\n		&= f\'(x)(k_1 - k_2)\n	}$\n</div>\nIt seems that whenever $k_1 = k_2$ the two are linearly dependent. This essentially states that given any function, a linearly independent function could be constructed from the one given by performing a vertical translation. Of course this does not hold true if:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 0 \\implies f(x) = C\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $C$ is any real number.'),(203,'Example_10',10,93,'Given the two functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = f(x)g(x) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y_2(x) = \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x),g(x) \\in C^1$ and $g(x) \\neq 0$, determine what condition makes the two linearly dependent.','Looking at the Wronskian:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		W(y_1,y_2) &= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			y_1 & y_2 \\\\\n			y_1\' & y_2\'\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\det \\begin{pmatrix}\n			f(x)g(x) & \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n			f\'(x)g(x) + f(x)g\'(x) & \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) - f(x)g\'(x)}{g^2(x)}\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{f(x)f\'(x)g(x) - f^2(x)g\'(x)}{g(x)} - f(x)f\'(x) \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{f^2(x)g\'(x)}{g(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom this it seems that in order to make the two functions linearly dependent, they must satisfy:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = f^2(x)g\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich implies that either:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 0 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{or} \\hspace{.5cm} g(x) = C\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $C$ is any real number.'),(204,'Example_1',1,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 4y\' + 4y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution.','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= ve^{2x} \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'e^{2x} + 2ve^{2x} \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'e^{2x} + 4v\'e^{2x} + 4ve^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y_2\'\' - 4y_2\' + 4y_2 \\\\\n		0 &= (v\'\'e^{2x} + 4v\'e^{2x} + 4ve^{2x}) - 4(v\'e^{2x} + 2ve^{2x}) + 4(ve^{2x}) \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\'e^{2x} \\\\\n		v\'\' &= 0 \\\\\n		v\' &= C_1 \\\\\n		v &= C_1x + C_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = ve^{2x} = (C_1x + C_2)e^{2x} = C_1xe^{2x} + C_2e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = xe^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(205,'Example_2',2,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\newcommand{\\sech}{\\mathop{\\rm sech}\\nolimits}\n		y_1(x) = \\cosh(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution.','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= v\\cosh(x) \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'\\cosh(x) + v\\sinh(x) \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'\\cosh(x) + 2v\'\\sinh(x) + v\\cosh(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y_2\'\' - y_2 \\\\\n		0 &= (v\'\'\\cosh(x) + 2v\'\\sinh(x) + v\\cosh(x)) - v\\cosh(x) \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\'\\cosh(x) + 2v\'\\sinh(x) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\'\\cosh(x) + 2v\'\\sinh(x) \\\\\n		0 &= w\'\\cosh(x) + 2w\\sinh(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx}\\cosh(x) &= -2w\\sinh(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= -2\\tanh(x) dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= \\int -2\\tanh(x) dx \\\\\n		\\ln|w| &= -2\\ln|\\cosh(x)| + C \\\\\n		w &= D_1\\sech^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1\\sech^2(x) \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int \\sech^2(x) dx \\\\\n		v &= D_1\\tanh(x) + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = v\\cosh(x) = D_1\\sinh(x) + D_2\\cosh(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = \\sinh(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(206,'Example_3',3,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2y\'\' + 2xy\' - 6y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution.','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= vx^2 \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'x^2 + 2vx \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'x^2 + 4v\'x + 2v\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= x^2y_2\'\' + 2xy_2\' - 6y \\\\\n		0 &= x^2(v\'\'x^2 + 4v\'x + 2v) + 2x(v\'x^2 + 2vx) - 6vx^2 \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\'x^4 + 6v\'x^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\'x^4 + 6v\'x^3 \\\\\n		0 &= w\'x^4 + 6wx^3 \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx}x^4 &= -6wx^3 \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= -\\frac{6}{x} dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= \\int -\\frac{6}{x} dx \\\\\n		\\ln|w| &= -6\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		w &= D_1x^{-6}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1x^{-6} \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int x^{-6} dx \\\\\n		v &= \\frac{D_1}{-5} x^{-5} + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = vx^2 = \\Big( \\frac{D_1}{-5} x^{-5} + D_2 \\Big)x^2 = -\\frac{D_1}{5}x^{-3} + D_2x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = x^{-3}\n	}$\n</div>'),(207,'Example_4',4,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		xy\'\' + y\' = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = \\ln(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution.','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= v\\ln(x) \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'\\ln(x) + vx^{-1} \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'\\ln(x) + 2v\'x^{-1} - vx^{-2}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= xy_2\'\' + y_2\' \\\\\n		0 &= x(v\'\'\\ln(x) + 2v\'x^{-1} - vx^{-2}) + (v\'\\ln(x) + vx^{-1}) \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\'x\\ln(x) + v\'(\\ln(x) + 2)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\'x\\ln(x) + v\'(\\ln(x) + 2) \\\\\n		0 &= w\'x\\ln(x) + w(\\ln(x) + 2) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx}x\\ln(x) &= -w(\\ln(x) + 2) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= -\\frac{\\ln(x) + 2}{x\\ln(x)} dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= -\\int \\Big( \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{2}{x\\ln(x)} \\Big) dx \\\\\n		\\ln|w| &= -\\ln|x| - 2\\ln|\\ln(x)| + C \\\\\n		w &= \\frac{D_1}{x\\ln^2(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere dropping the absolute value is allowed since the original domain is already restricted to the positive real numbers due to the first solution. Now to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= \\frac{D_1}{x\\ln^2(x)} \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int \\frac{1}{x\\ln^2(x)} dx \\\\\n		v &= -\\frac{D_1}{\\ln(x)} + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = vx^2 = \\Big( -\\frac{D_1}{\\ln(x)} + D_2 \\Big)\\ln(x) = -D_1 + D_2\\ln(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(208,'Example_5',5,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 9y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = \\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution.','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= v\\sin(3x) \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'\\sin(3x) + 3v\\cos(3x) \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'\\sin(3x) + 6v\'\\cos(3x) - 9v\\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y_2\'\' + 9y_2 \\\\\n		0 &= (v\'\'\\sin(3x) + 6v\'\\cos(3x) - 9v\\sin(3x)) + 9v\\sin(3x) \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\'\\sin(3x) + 6v\'\\cos(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\'\\sin(3x) + 6v\'\\cos(3x) \\\\\n		0 &= w\'\\sin(3x) + 6w\\cos(3x) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx}\\sin(3x) &= -6w\\cos(3x) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= -\\frac{6\\cos(3x)}{\\sin(3x)} dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= \\int -\\frac{6\\cos(3x)}{\\sin(3x)} dx \\\\\n		\\ln|w| &= -2\\ln|\\sin(3x)| + C \\\\\n		w &= D_1\\csc^2(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1\\csc^2(3x) \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int \\csc^2(3x) dx \\\\\n		v &= -\\frac{1}{3}D_1\\cot(3x) + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = v\\sin(3x) = \\Big( -\\frac{1}{3}D_1\\cot(3x) + D_2 \\Big)\\sin(3x) = -\\frac{D_1}{3}\\cos(3x) + D_2\\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = \\cos(3x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(209,'Example_6',6,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 4y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = e^{-2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution.','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= ve^{-2x} \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'e^{-2x} - 2ve^{-2x} \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'e^{-2x} - 4v\'e^{-2x} + 4ve^{-2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y_2\'\' - 4y_2 \\\\\n		0 &= (v\'\'e^{-2x} - 4v\'e^{-2x} + 4ve^{-2x}) - 4(ve^{-2x}) \\\\\n		0 &= (v\'\' - 4v\')e^{-2x} \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\' - 4v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\' - 4v\' \\\\\n		0 &= w\' - 4w \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx} &= 4w \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= 4 dx \\\\ \n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= \\int 4 dx \\\\ \n		\\ln|w| &= 4x + C \\\\\n		w &= D_1e^{4x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1e^{4x} \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int e^{4x} dx \\\\\n		v &= \\frac{D_1}{4}e^{4x} + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = ve^{-2x} = \\Big( \\frac{D_1}{4}e^{4x} + D_2 \\Big)e^{-2x} = \\frac{D_1}{4}e^{2x} + D_2e^{-2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(210,'Example_7',7,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		xy\'\' - xy\' + y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nverify that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = x\n	}$\n</div>\nis a solution and use reduction of order to determine a second solution in the form of an infinite series.','First to verify:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= xy_1\'\' - xy_1\' + y_1 \\\\\n		0 &= x(0) - x(1) + (x) \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= vx \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'x + v \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'x + 2v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= xy_2\'\' - xy_2\' + y_2 \\\\\n		0 &= x(v\'\'x + 2v\') - x(v\'x + v) + vx \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\'x^2 + v\'(2x - x^2)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\'x^2 + v\'(2x - x^2) \\\\\n		0 &= w\'x^2 + w(2x - x^2) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx}x^2 &= w(x^2 - 2x) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= 1 - \\frac{2}{x} dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= \\int \\Big( 1 - \\frac{2}{x} \\Big) dx \\\\\n		\\ln|w| &= x - 2\\ln|x| + C \\\\\n		w &= D_1\\frac{e^x}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1\\frac{e^x}{x^2} \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int \\frac{e^x}{x^2} dx \\\\\n		v &= D_1\\int \\Bigg( \\sum_{n = 0}^\\infty \\frac{x^{n - 2}}{n!} \\Bigg) dx \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{n = 0}^\\infty \\frac{D_1}{n!} \\int x^{n - 2} dx \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{n = 0}^\\infty \\frac{D_1}{(n - 1)n!} x^{n - 1} + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the interchange of the order with the summation and integration is allowed so long as we are inside the radius of convergence. With this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = vx = \\Big( \\sum_{n = 0}^\\infty \\frac{D_1}{(n - 1)n!} x^{n - 1} + D_2 \\Big)x = \\sum_{n = 0}^\\infty \\frac{D_1}{(n - 1)n!} x^n + D_2x\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = \\sum_{n = 0}^\\infty \\frac{x^n}{(n - 1)n!}\n	}$\n</div>'),(211,'Example_8',8,94,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + ay\' + by = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a,b \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nUse reduction of order to determine a second solution. What does the solution look like when $2m + a = 0$? How about when $m \\in \\mathbb{C}$?','For reduction of order we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= ve^{mx} \\\\\n		y_2\' &= v\'e^{mx} + mve^{mx} \\\\\n		y_2\'\' &= v\'\'e^{mx} + 2mv\'e^{mx} + m^2ve^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging this in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y_2\'\' + ay_2\' + by_2 \\\\\n		0 &= (v\'\'e^{mx} + 2mv\'e^{mx} + m^2ve^{mx}) + a(v\'e^{mx} + mve^{mx}) + bve^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= e^{mx}\\Big[ v\'\' + v\'(2m + a) + v(y_1\'\' + ay_1\' + by_1) \\Big] \\\\\n		0 &= v\'\' + v\'(2m + a)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow make the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w = v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= v\'\' + v\'(2m + a) \\\\\n		0 &= w\' + w(2m + a) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dx} &= -w(2m + a) \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{w} &= -(2m + a) dx \\\\\n		\\int \\frac{dw}{w} &= \\int -(2m + a) dx \\\\\n		\\ln|w| &= -(2m + a)x + C \\\\\n		w &= D_1e^{-(2m + a)x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to solve for $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1e^{-(2m + a)x} \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int e^{-(2m + a)x} dx \\\\\n		v &= \\frac{D_1}{-(2m + a)}e^{-(2m + a)x} + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = ve^{mx} = \\Big( \\frac{D_1}{-(2m + a)}e^{-(2m + a)x} + D_2 \\Big)e^{mx} = \\frac{D_1}{-(2m + a)}e^{-(m + a)x} + D_2e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = e^{-(m + a)x}\n	}$\n</div>\nOf course this assumed that $2m + a \\neq 0$. If this was not the case, then:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' &= w \\\\\n		\\frac{dv}{dx} &= D_1 \\\\\n		\\int dv &= D_1\\int dx \\\\\n		v &= D_1x + D_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the second solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = ve^{mx} = \\Big( D_1x + D_2 \\Big)e^{mx} = D_1xe^{mx} + D_2e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis seems to take on the form of the homogeneous solution, but so if we want the second solution that would be part of the fundamental set it actually is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 = xe^x\n	}$\n</div>\nLastly if $m \\in \\mathbb{C}$ and we let $m = k + li$ where $l \\neq 0$, then $m + a \\in \\mathbb{C}$. This implies that the original solution when assuming that $2m + a \\neq 0$ will remain the same except the for the fact that the constant will be imaginary instead of real.'),(212,'Example_9',9,94,'Given the non-linear first order differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = -\\frac{4}{x^2} - \\frac{1}{x}y + y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand a solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_1(x) = \\frac{2}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nAssume:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2(x) = y_1(x) + v\n	}$\n</div>\nand determine the second solution using this substitution.','First we need:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= \\frac{2}{x} + v \\\\\n		y_2\' &= -\\frac{2}{x^2} + v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich when plugged in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2\' &= -\\frac{4}{x^2} - \\frac{1}{x}y_2 + y_2^2 \\\\\n		-\\frac{2}{x^2} + v\' &= -\\frac{4}{x^2} - \\frac{1}{x}\\Big( \\frac{2}{x} + v \\Big) + \\Big( \\frac{2}{x} + v \\Big)^2 \\\\\n		-\\frac{2}{x^2} + v\' &= -\\frac{6}{x^2} - \\frac{1}{x}v + \\Big( \\frac{4}{x^2} + v^2 + \\frac{4}{x}v \\Big) \\\\\n		v\' &= \\frac{3}{x}v + v^2 \\\\\n		v\' - \\frac{3}{x}v &= v^2\n	}$\n</div>\na Bernoulli differential equation. Now making the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w &= v^{-1} \\\\\n		w\' &= -v^{-2}v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' - \\frac{3}{x}v &= v^2 \\\\\n		v^{-2}v\' - \\frac{3}{x}v^{-1} &= 1 \\\\\n		-w\' - \\frac{3}{x}w &= 1 \\\\\n		w\' + \\frac{3}{x}w &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\ngives a first order linear differential equation. First we need an integrating factor:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int \\frac{3}{x} dx} \\\\\n		&= e^{3\\ln|x|} \\\\\n		&= |x|^3 \\\\\n		&= x^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow multiplying through and solving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w\' + \\frac{3}{x}w &= -1 \\\\\n		x^3w\' + 3x^2w &= -x^3 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (x^3w) &= -x^3 \\\\\n		\\int d(x^3w) &= \\int -x^3 dx \\\\\n		x^3w &= -\\frac{1}{4}x^4 + C_1 \\\\\n		w &= -\\frac{1}{4}x + Cx^{-3}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we need to determine $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v^{-1} &= w \\\\\n		v &= w^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\Big( -\\frac{x}{4} + \\frac{C}{x^3} \\Big)^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can finally write down the second solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2(x) = \\frac{2}{x} + v = \\frac{2}{x} + \\Big( -\\frac{x}{4} + \\frac{C}{x^3} \\Big)^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(213,'Example_10',10,94,'The non-linear first order differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} = q_0(x) + q_1(x)y + q_2(x)y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as a Riccati equation. Assume you have some known solution, $y_1(x)$, and that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2(x) = y_1(x) + v\n	}$\n</div>\nUse this substitution to obtain the second solution.','First we need:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2 &= y_1 + v \\\\\n		y_2\' &= y_1\' + v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich when plugged in gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2\' &= q_0(x) + q_1(x)y_2 + q_2(x)y_2^2 \\\\\n		y_1\' + v\' &= q_0(x) + q_1(x)(y_1 + v) + q_2(x)(y_1 + v)^2 \\\\\n		y_1\' + v\' &= (q_0(x) + q_1(x)y_1 + q_2(x)y_1^2) + q_1(x)v + 2q_2(x)y_1v + q_2(x)v^2 \\\\\n		y_1\' + v\' &= y_1\' + q_1(x)v + 2q_2(x)y_1v + q_2(x)v^2 \\\\\n		v\' &= v(q_1(x) + 2q_2(x)y_1(x)) + q_2(x)v^2 \\\\\n		v\' + (-q_1(x) - 2q_2(x)y_1(x))v &= q_2(x)v^2\n	}$\n</div>\na Bernoulli differential equation. Now making the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w &= v^{-1} \\\\\n		w\' &= -v^{-2}v\'\n	}$\n</div>\nand plugging in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v\' + (-q_1(x) - 2q_2(x)y_1(x))v &= q_2(x)v^2 \\\\\n		v^{-2}v\' + (-q_1(x) - 2q_2(x)y_1(x))v^{-1} &= q_2(x) \\\\\n		-w\' - (q_1(x) + 2q_2(x)y_1(x))w &= q_2(x) \\\\\n		w\' + (q_1(x) + 2q_2(x)y_1(x))w &= -q_2(x)\n	}$\n</div>\ngives a first order linear differential equation. First we need an integrating factor:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mu &= e^{\\int (q_1(x) + 2q_2(x)y_1(x)) dx}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow multiplying through and solving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		w\' + (q_1(x) + 2q_2(x)y_1(x))w &= -q_2(x) \\\\\n		\\mu w\' + (q_1(x) + 2q_2(x)y_1(x))\\mu w &= -q_2(x)\\mu \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (w\\mu) &= -q_2(x)\\mu \\\\\n		\\int d(w\\mu) &= \\int -q_2(x)\\mu dx \\\\\n		w &= -\\mu^{-1} \\int q_2(x)\\mu dx + C\\mu^{-1} \n	}$\n</div>\nNow we need to determine $v$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		v^{-1} &= w \\\\\n		v &= w^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\Big( -\\mu^{-1} \\int q_2(x)\\mu dx + C\\mu^{-1} \\Big)^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can finally write down the second solution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_2(x) = y_1(x) + v = y_1(x) + \\Big( -\\mu^{-1} \\int q_2(x)\\mu dx + C\\mu^{-1} \\Big)^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(214,'Example_1',1,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y = e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 2me^{mx} - 3e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 2m - 3 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 1)(m - 3) \\\\\n		m &= -1, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = Ae^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{2x} &= y_{nh}\'\' - 2y_{nh}\' - 3y_{nh} \\\\\n		e^{2x} &= 4Ae^{2x} - 4Ae^{2x} - 3Ae^{2x} \\\\\n		e^{2x} &= -3Ae^{2x} \\\\\n		A &= -\\frac{1}{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{3x} - \\frac{1}{3}e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(215,'Example_2',2,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 3y\' - 10y = -4\\cos(x) + 7\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 10y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 3me^{mx} - 10e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 3m - 10 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 2)(m - 5) \\\\\n		m &= -2, 5\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-2x} + c_2e^{5x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = A\\cos(x) + B\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-4\\cos(x) + 7\\sin(x) &= y_{nh}\'\' - 3y_{nh}\' - 10y_{nh} \\\\\n		-4\\cos(x) + 7\\sin(x) &= (-A\\cos(x) - B\\sin(x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3(-A\\sin(x) + B\\cos(x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 10(A\\cos(x) + B\\sin(x)) \\\\\n		-4\\cos(x) + 7\\sin(x) &= (-11A - 3B)\\cos(x) + (3A - 11B)\\sin(x) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nThis can be rewritten in matrix form and using the inverse a solution can be obtained:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			-11 & -3 \\\\\n			3 & -11\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			A \\\\\n			B\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-4 \\\\\n			7\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			A \\\\\n			B\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\frac{1}{130} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-11 & 3 \\\\\n			-3 & -11\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-4 \\\\\n			7\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n			-\\frac{1}{2}\n		\\end{pmatrix}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-2x} + c_2e^{5x} + \\frac{1}{2}\\cos(x) - \\frac{1}{2}\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(216,'Example_3',3,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 6y\' + 9y = e^{2x}\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 6y\' + 9y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 6me^{mx} + 9e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 6m + 9 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 3)^2 \\\\\n		m &= 3\n	}$\n</div>\nto get one real value for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{3x} + c_2xe^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = e^{2x}[A\\sin(x) + B\\cos(x)]\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{2x}\\sin(x) &= y_{nh}\'\' - 6y_{nh}\' + 9y_{nh} \\\\\n		e^{2x}\\sin(x) &= e^{2x}[(3A - 4B)\\sin(x) + (4A + 3B)\\cos(x)] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 6e^{2x}[(2A - B)\\sin(x) + (A + 2B)\\cos(x)] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 9e^{2x}[A\\sin(x) + B\\cos(x)] \\\\\n		e^{2x}\\sin(x) &= (2B)e^{2x}\\sin(x) + (-2A)e^{2x}\\cos(x) \\\\\n		A &= 0 \\\\\n		B &= \\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{3x} + c_2xe^{3x} + \\frac{1}{2}e^{2x}\\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(217,'Example_4',4,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 9y = 39xe^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 9y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 9e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 9 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 3i)(m + 3i) \\\\\n		m &= \\pm 3i\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two distinct complex values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1\\cos(3x) + c_2\\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = (Ax + B)e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		39xe^{2x} &= y_{nh}\'\' + 9y_{nh} \\\\\n		39xe^{2x} &= 4(Ax + A + B)e^{2x} + 9(Ax + B)e^{2x} \\\\\n		39xe^{2x} &= 13Axe^{2x} + (4A + 13B)e^{2x} \\\\\n		A &= 3 \\\\\n		B &= -\\frac{12}{13}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1\\cos(3x) + c_2\\sin(3x) + \\Big( 3x - \\frac{12}{13} \\Big)e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(218,'Example_5',5,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 4y\' = 4xe^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 4y\' \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 4me^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 4m \\\\\n		0 &= m(m + 4) \\\\\n		m &= -4, 0\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-4x} + c_2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = (Ax + B)e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4xe^{2x} &= y_{nh}\'\' + 4y_{nh}\'\' \\\\\n		4xe^{2x} &= 4e^{2x}(Ax + A + B) + 4e^{2x}(2Ax + A + 2B) \\\\\n		4xe^{2x} &= (12A)xe^{2x} + (8A + 12B)e^{2x} \\\\\n		A &= \\frac{1}{3} \\\\\n		B &= -\\frac{2}{9}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-4x} + c_2 + \\frac{1}{9}(3x - 2)e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(219,'Example_6',6,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y = 28e^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 2me^{mx} - 3e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 2m - 3 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 1)(m - 3) \\\\\n		m &= -1, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = Axe^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		28e^{3x} &= y_{nh}\'\' - 2y_{nh}\' - 3y_{nh} \\\\\n		28e^{3x} &= 3Ae^{3x}(3x + 2) - 2Ae^{3x}(3x + 1) - 3Axe^{3x} \\\\\n		28e^{3x} &= 4Ae^{3x} \\\\\n		A &= 7\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{3x} + 7xe^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(220,'Example_7',7,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 5y\' + 6y = x^2e^{-7x} + 2e^{-7x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 5y\' + 6y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 5me^{mx} + 6e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 5m + 6 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 2)(m - 3) \\\\\n		m &= 2, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{2x} + c_2e^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = (Ax^2 + Bx + C)e^{-7x}\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2e^{-7x} + 2e^{-7x} &= y_{nh}\'\' - 5y_{nh}\' + 6y_{nh} \\\\\n		x^2e^{-7x} + 2e^{-7x} &= e^{-7x}(49Ax^2 - 28Ax + 2A + 49Bx - 14B + 49C) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 5e^{-7x}(7Ax^2 - 2Ax + 7Bx - B + 7C) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 6e^{-7x}(Ax^2 + Bx + C) \\\\\n		x^2e^{-7x} + 2e^{-7x} &= (90A)x^2e^{-7x} + (-38A + 90B)xe^{-7x} + (2A - 19B + 90C)e^{-7x} \\\\\n		A &= \\frac{1}{90} \\\\\n		B &= \\frac{19}{4050} \\\\\n		C &= \\frac{8371}{364500}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{2x} + c_2e^{3x} + \\Big( \\frac{1}{90}x^2 + \\frac{19}{4050}x + \\frac{8371}{364500} \\Big)e^{-7x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(221,'Example_8',8,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 25y = 25x^4 - 25 + e^x \n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 25y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 25e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 25 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 5i)(m + 5i) \\\\\n		m &= \\pm 5i\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1\\cos(5x) + c_2\\sin(5x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = Ax^4 + Bx^3 + Cx^2 + Dx + E + Fe^x\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		25x^4 - 25 + e^x  &= y_{nh}\'\' + 25y_{nh} \\\\\n		25x^4 - 25 + e^x  &= (12Ax^2 + 6Bx + 2C + Fe^x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 25(Ax^4 + Bx^3 + Cx^2 + Dx + E + Fe^x) \\\\\n		25x^4 - 25 + e^x  &= (25A)x^4 + (25B)x^3 + (12A + 25C)x^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (6B + 25D)x + (2C + 25E) + (26F)e^x \\\\\n		A &= 1 \\\\\n		B &= 0 \\\\\n		C &= -\\frac{12}{25} \\\\\n		D &= 0 \\\\\n		E &= -\\frac{601}{625} \\\\\n		F &= \\frac{1}{26}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1\\cos(5x) + c_2\\sin(5x) + x^4 - \\frac{12}{25}x^2 - \\frac{601}{625} + \\frac{1}{26}e^x\n	}$\n</div>'),(222,'Example_9',9,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 9y = x^3\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) = 0 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'(0) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 9y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 9e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 9 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 3i)(m - 3o) \\\\\n		m &= \\pm 3i\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two complex distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1\\cos(3x) + c_2\\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = Ax^3 + Bx^2 + Cx + D\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^3 &= y_{nh}\'\' + 9y_{nh} \\\\\n		x^3 &= (6Ax + 2B) + 9(Ax^3 + Bx^2 + Cx + D) \\\\\n		x^3 &= 9Ax^3 + 9Bx^2 + (6A + 9C)x + (2B + 9D) \\\\\n		A &= \\frac{1}{9} \\\\\n		B &= 0 \\\\\n		C &= \\frac{2}{27} \\\\\n		D &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1\\cos(3x) + c_2\\sin(3x) + \\frac{1}{9}x^3 + \\frac{2}{27}x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) = -3c_1\\sin(3x) + 3c_2\\cos(3x) + \\frac{1}{3}x^2 + \\frac{2}{27}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) &= c_1\\cos(3(0)) + c_2\\sin(3(0)) + \\frac{1}{9}(0)^3 + \\frac{2}{27}(0) = 0 \\\\\n		y\'(0) &= -3c_1\\sin(3(0)) + 3c_2\\cos(3(0)) + \\frac{1}{3}(0)^2 + \\frac{2}{27} = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom the equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c_1 &= 0 \\\\\n		c_2 &= -\\frac{2}{81}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = -\\frac{2}{81}\\sin(3x) + \\frac{1}{9}x^3 + \\frac{2}{27}x\n	}$\n</div>'),(223,'Example_10',10,95,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' = 6xe^x\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) = 0 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'(0) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a non-homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the addition of the homogeneous and non-homogeneous solutions. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in to solve the homogeneous portion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 \\\\\n		m &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nto get one real value for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1 + c_2x\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the non-homogeneous solution, using the method of undetermined coefficients we will guess that the solution takes on the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_{nh}(x) = ((Ax + B)\\sin(x) + (Cx + D)\\cos(x))e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging into the differential equation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6xe^x\\sin(x) &= y_{nh}\'\' \\\\\n		6xe^x\\sin(x) &= (-2C)xe^x\\sin(x) + (2A)xe^x\\cos(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (2A - 2C - 2D)e^x\\sin(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (2A + 2B + 2C)e^x\\cos(x) \\\\\n		C &= -3 \\\\\n		A &= 0 \\\\\n		D &= 3 \\\\\n		B &= 3\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1 + c_2x + (3\\sin(x) + 3(1 - x)\\cos(x))e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) = c_2 + 3e^x(x\\sin(x) + (1 - x)\\cos(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) &= c_1 + c_2(0) + (3\\sin(0) + 3(1 - (0))\\cos(0))e^0 = 0 \\\\\n		y\'(0) &= c_2 + 3e^0(x\\sin(0) + (1 - (0))\\cos(0)) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom the equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c_1 &= -3 \\\\\n		c_2 &= -3\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = -3 - 3x + (3\\sin(x) + 3(1 - x)\\cos(x))e^x\n	}$\n</div>'),(224,'Example_1',1,96,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 3y\' - 4y = 10e^{4x}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution using the annihilator method.','We begin by noting that the annihilator operator from the table is going to be given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D - 4\n	}$\n</div>\nNow rewriting the differential equation using operators and applying the annihilator to both sides gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		10e^{4x} &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 4y \\\\\n		10e^{4x} &= (D^2 - 3D - 4)y \\\\\n		(D - 4)10e^{4x} &= (D - 4)(D^2 - 3D - 4)y \\\\\n		0 &= (D - 4)(D^2 - 3D - 4)y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are left with solving the characteristic polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (\\lambda - 4)(\\lambda^2 - 3\\lambda - 4) \\\\\n		0 &= (\\lambda - 4)(\\lambda - 4)(\\lambda + 1) \\\\\n		\\lambda &= -1, 4\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere one of the roots repeats. Knowing this we can write down the fundamental set of solutions as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ e^{-x}, e^{4x}, xe^{4x} \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now form our general solution as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{4x} + c_3xe^{4x}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into the differential equation to determine the constants for the non-homogeneous component:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		10e^{4x} &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 4y \\\\\n		10e^{4x} &= (c_1e^{-x} + 16c_2e^{4x} + c_3(16x + 8)e^{4x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3(-c_1e^{-x} + 4c_2e^{4x} + c_3(1 + 4x)e^{4x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 4(c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{4x} + c_3xe^{4x}) \\\\\n		10e^{4x} &= 5c_3e^{4x} \\\\\n		c_3 &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{4x} + 2xe^{4x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(225,'Example_2',2,96,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 3y\' - 4y = 3x^2\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution using the annihilator method.','We begin by noting that the annihilator operator from the table is going to be given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow rewriting the differential equation using operators and applying the annihilator to both sides gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3x^2 &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 4y \\\\\n		3x^2 &= (D^2 - 3D - 4)y \\\\\n		D^3(3x^2) &= (D^3)(D^2 - 3D - 4)y \\\\\n		0 &= (D^3)(D^2 - 3D - 4)y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are left with solving the characteristic polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (\\lambda^3)(\\lambda^2 - 3\\lambda - 4) \\\\\n		0 &= (\\lambda^3)(\\lambda - 4)(\\lambda + 1) \\\\\n		\\lambda &= -1, 0, 4\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere one of the roots repeats three times. Knowing this we can write down the fundamental set of solutions as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ e^{-x}, e^{4x}, 1, x, x^2 \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now form our general solution as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{4x} + c_3 + c_4x + c_5x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into the differential equation to determine the constants for the non-homogeneous component:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3x^2 &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 4y \\\\\n		3x^2 &= (c_1e^{-x} + 16c_2e^{4x} + 2c_5) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3(-c_1e^{-x} + 4c_2e^{4x} + c_4 + 2c_5x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 4(c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{4x} + c_3 + c_4x + c_5x^2) \\\\\n		3x^2 &= (-4c_5)x^2 + (-4c_4 - 6c_5)x \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (-4c_3 - 3c_4 + 2c_5) \\\\\n		c_5 &= -\\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		c_4 &= \\frac{9}{8} \\\\\n		c_3 &= -\\frac{39}{32}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{4x} - \\frac{39}{32} + \\frac{9}{8}x - \\frac{3}{4}x^2\n	}$\n</div>'),(226,'Example_3',3,96,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3y\'\' - y\' - 2y = 2x^2 + 6x - 4\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution using the annihilator method.','We begin by noting that the annihilator operator from the table is going to be given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow rewriting the differential equation using operators and applying the annihilator to both sides gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2x^2 + 6x - 4 &= 3y\'\' - y\' - 2y \\\\\n		2x^2 + 6x - 4 &= (3D^2 - D - 2)y \\\\\n		D^3(2x^2 + 6x - 4) &= (D^3)(3D^2 - D - 2)y \\\\\n		0 &= (D^3)(D^2 - D - 2)y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are left with solving the characteristic polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (\\lambda^3)(3\\lambda^2 - \\lambda - 2) \\\\\n		0 &= (\\lambda^3)(3\\lambda + 2)(\\lambda - 1) \\\\\n		\\lambda &= -\\frac{2}{3}, 0, 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere one of the roots repeats three times. Knowing this we can write down the fundamental set of solutions as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ e^{-x}, e^{-\\frac{2}{3}x}, 1, x, x^2 \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now form our general solution as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{-\\frac{2}{3}x} + c_3 + c_4x + c_5x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into the differential equation to determine the constants for the non-homogeneous component:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2x^2 + 6x - 4 &= 3y\'\' - y\' - 2y \\\\\n		2x^2 + 6x - 4 &= 3(c_1e^{-x} + \\frac{4}{9}c_2e^{-\\frac{2}{3}x} + 2c_5) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - (-c_1e^{-x} - \\frac{2}{3}c_2e^{-\\frac{2}{3}x} + c_4 + 2c_5x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 2(c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{-\\frac{2}{3}x} + c_3 + c_4x + c_5x^2) \\\\\n		2x^2 + 6x - 4 &= (-2c_5)x^2 + (-2c_4 - 2c_5)x + (-2c_3 - c_4 + 6c_5) \\\\\n		c_5 &= -1 \\\\\n		c_4 &= -2 \\\\\n		c_3 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2e^{-\\frac{2}{3}x} - 2x - x^2\n	}$\n</div>'),(227,'Example_4',4,96,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 3y\' - 40y = \\sin(2x)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution using the annihilator method.','We begin by noting that the annihilator operator from the table is going to be given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D^2 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nNow rewriting the differential equation using operators and applying the annihilator to both sides gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(2x) &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 40y \\\\\n		\\sin(2x) &= (D^2 - 3D - 40)y \\\\\n		(D^2 + 4)\\sin(2x) &= (D^2 + 4)(D^2 - 3D - 40)y \\\\\n		0 &= (D^2 + 4)(D^2 - 3D - 40)y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are left with solving the characteristic polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (\\lambda^2 + 4)(\\lambda^2 - 3\\lambda - 40) \\\\\n		0 &= (\\lambda + 2i)(\\lambda - 2i)(\\lambda + 5)(\\lambda - 8) \\\\\n		\\lambda &= -5, 8, \\pm 2i\n	}$\n</div>\nKnowing this we can write down the fundamental set of solutions as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ e^{-5x}, e^{8x}, \\sin(2x), \\cos(2x) \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now form our general solution as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-5x} + c_2e^{8x} + c_3\\sin(2x) + c_4\\cos(2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into the differential equation to determine the constants for the non-homogeneous component:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(2x) &= y\'\' - 3y\' - 40y \\\\\n		\\sin(2x) &= (25c_1e^{-5x} + 64c_2e^{8x} - 4c_3\\sin(2x) - 4c_4\\cos(2x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3(-5c_1e^{-5x} + 8c_2e^{8x} + 2c_3\\cos(2x) - 2c_4\\sin(2x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 40(c_1e^{-5x} + c_2e^{8x} + c_3\\sin(2x) + c_4\\cos(2x)) \\\\\n		\\sin(2x) &= (-44c_3 + 6c_4)\\sin(2x) + (-6c_3 - 44c_4)\\cos(2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich can be rewritten in matrix form and using the inverse a unique solution can be obtained:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			-44 & 6 \\\\\n			-6 & -44 \n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			c_3 \\\\\n			c_4\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			1 \\\\\n			0\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			c_3 \\\\\n			c_4\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\frac{1}{1972} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-44 & -6 \\\\\n			6 & -44\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			1 \\\\\n			0\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-\\frac{44}{1972} \\\\\n			\\frac{6}{1972}\n		\\end{pmatrix}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-5x} + c_2e^{8x} - \\frac{11}{493}\\sin(2x) + \\frac{3}{986}\\cos(2x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(228,'Example_5',5,96,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + y\' = 3\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution using the annihilator method.','We begin by noting that the annihilator operator from the table is going to be given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D\n	}$\n</div>\nNow rewriting the differential equation using operators and applying the annihilator to both sides gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3 &= y\'\' + y\' \\\\\n		3 &= (D^2 + D)y \\\\\n		D(3) &= (D)(D^2 + D)y \\\\\n		0 &= (D)(D^2 + D)y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are left with solving the characteristic polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (\\lambda)(\\lambda^2 + \\lambda) \\\\\n		0 &= (\\lambda^2)(\\lambda + 1) \\\\\n		\\lambda &= -1, 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere one of the roots repeats twice. Knowing this we can write down the fundamental set of solutions as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ e^{-x}, 1, x \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now form our general solution as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2 + c_3x\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into the differential equation to determine the constants for the non-homogeneous component:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		3 &= y\'\' + y\' \\\\\n		3 &= (c_1e^{-x}) + (-c_1e^{-x} + c_3) \\\\\n		c_3 &= 3\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1e^{-x} + c_2 + 3x\n	}$\n</div>'),(229,'Example_6',6,96,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y = 4e^{-x} - 9\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution using the annihilator method.','We begin by noting that the annihilator operator from the table is going to be given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = (D + 1)(D)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow rewriting the differential equation using operators and applying the annihilator to both sides gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4e^{-x} - 9 &= y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y \\\\\n		4e^{-x} - 9 &= (D^2 - 2D - 3)y \\\\\n		(D + 1)(D)(4e^{-x} - 9) &= (D + 1)(D)(D^2 - 2D - 3)y \\\\\n		0 &= (D + 1)(D)(D^2 - 2D - 3)y\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are left with solving the characteristic polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (\\lambda + 1)(\\lambda)(\\lambda^2 - 2\\lambda - 3) \\\\\n		0 &= (\\lambda + 1)^2(\\lambda)(\\lambda - 3) \\\\\n		\\lambda &= -1, 0, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere one of the roots repeats twice. Knowing this we can write down the fundamental set of solutions as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{S} = \\{ 1, e^{3x}, e^{-x}, xe^{-x} \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now form our general solution as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = c_1 + c_2e^{3x} + c_3e^{-x} + c_4xe^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into the differential equation to determine the constants for the non-homogeneous component:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4e^{-x} - 9 &= y\'\' - 2y\' - 3y \\\\\n		4e^{-x} - 9 &= (9c_2e^{3x} + c_3e^{-x} + c_4e^{-x}(x - 2)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 2(3c_2e^{3x} - c_3e^{-x} + c_4e^{-x}(1 - x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3(c_1 + c_2e^{3x} + c_3e^{-x} + c_4xe^{-x}) \\\\\n		4e^{-x} - 9 &= -3c_1 - 4c_4e^{-x} \\\\\n		c_1 &= 3 \\\\\n		c_4 &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the general solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = 3 + c_2e^{3x} + c_3e^{-x} - xe^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(230,'Example_7',7,96,'Prove that the annihilator operator for:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = k_1\\cosh(\\alpha x) + k_2\\sinh(\\alpha x) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.5cm} k_1,k_2,\\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D^2 - \\alpha^2\n	}$\n</div>','The easiest way to prove is to simply plug in to show that it goes to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D)f(x) &= (D^2 - \\alpha^2)(k_1\\cosh(\\alpha x) + k_2\\sinh(\\alpha x)) \\\\\n		&= D^2(k_1\\cosh(\\alpha x) + k_2\\sinh(\\alpha x)) - \\alpha^2(k_1\\cosh(\\alpha x) + k_2\\sinh(\\alpha x)) \\\\\n		&= \\alpha^2(k_1\\cosh(\\alpha x) + k_2\\sinh(\\alpha x)) - \\alpha^2(k_1\\cosh(\\alpha x) + k_2\\sinh(\\alpha x)) \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(231,'Example_8',8,96,'Prove that the annihilator operator for:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sum_{i = 0}^n a_ix^i \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.5cm} a_1,a_2,\\dots,a_n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D^{n + 1}\n	}$\n</div>','The easiest way to prove is to simply plug in to show that it goes to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D)f(x) &= D^{n + 1} \\Bigg[ \\sum_{i = 0}^n a_ix^i \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= D^{n + 1} (a_0 + a_1x + a_2x^2 + \\dots + a_{n - 1}x^{n - 1} + a_nx^n) \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(232,'Example_9',9,96,'Derive the annihilator operator for:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = ke^{\\alpha x} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.5cm} k,\\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing only the derivative operator and its corresponding eigenvalue and eigenfunction.','We begin by restating that for the derivative operator we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		Df(x) = \\alpha f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x)$ is the eigenfunction and $\\alpha$ is the associated eigenvalue. Now notice that if we bring everything to one side:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		Df(x) - \\alpha f(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		(D - \\alpha)f(x) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwe get the annihilator operator for the derivative\'s eigenfunction. We already know that the eigenfunction happens to be exactly the function given to us, so the above annihilator is the one we want.'),(233,'Example_10',10,96,'Prove that the annihilator operator for:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sum_{i = 1}^n a_ie^{ix} \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.5cm} a_1,a_2,\\dots,a_n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = \\prod_{i \\in S} (D - i)\n	}$\n</div>','First we note that for the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = ke^{\\alpha x}\n	}$\n</div>\nthe annihilator is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D) = D - \\alpha\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this in mind, the easiest way to prove is to simply plug in to show that it goes to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(D)f(x) &= \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S} (D - i) \\Bigg] \\Bigg[ \\sum_{i \\in S} a_ie^{ix} \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S} (D - i) \\Bigg] (a_{i_0}e^{i_0x} + a_{i_1}e^{i_1x} + \\dots + a_{i_n}e^{i_nx}) \\\\\n		&= \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S \\setminus \\{i_0\\}} (D - i) \\Bigg] (D - i_0)(a_{i_0}e^{i_0x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S \\setminus \\{i_1\\}} (D - i) \\Bigg] (D - i_1)(a_{i_1}e^{i_1x}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\dots + \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S \\setminus \\{i_n\\}} (D - i) \\Bigg] (D - i_n)(a_{i_n}e^{i_nx}) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{k \\in S} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S \\setminus \\{i_k\\}} (D - i) \\Bigg] (D - i_k)(a_{i_k}e^{i_kx}) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{k \\in S} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i \\in S \\setminus \\{i_k\\}} (D - i) \\Bigg] (0) \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the breakup of the product is allowed since it does not matter in which order we apply the annihilators since the derivative operator commutes with itself.'),(234,'Example_1',1,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 11y\' + 24y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 11y\' + 24y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 11me^{mx} + 24e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 11m + 24 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 8)(m + 3) \\\\\n		m &= -8, -3\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-8x} + c_2e^{-3x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(235,'Example_2',2,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 3y\' - 10y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) = 4 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'(0) = -2\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 3y\' - 10y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 3me^{mx} - 10e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 3m - 10 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 2)(m + 5) \\\\\n		m &= -5, 2\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-5x} + c_2e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h\'(x) = -5c_1e^{-5x} + 2c_2e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(0) &= c_1e^{-5(0)} + c_2e^{2(0)} = 4 \\\\\n		y_h\'(0) &= -5c_1e^{-5(0)} + 2c_2e^{2(0)} = -2\n	}$\n</div>\nThis can be rewritten in matrix form and using the inverse a solution can be obtained:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			1 & 1 \\\\\n			-5 & 2\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			c_1 \\\\\n			c_2\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			4 \\\\\n			-2\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			c_1 \\\\\n			c_2\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\frac{1}{7} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			2 & -1 \\\\\n			5 & 1\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			4 \\\\\n			-2\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			\\frac{10}{7} \\\\\n			\\frac{18}{7}\n		\\end{pmatrix}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\frac{10}{7}e^{-5x} + \\frac{18}{7}e^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(236,'Example_3',3,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4y\'\' - 5y\' = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(-2) = 0 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'(-2) = 7\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 4y\'\' - 5y\' \\\\\n		0 &= 4m^2e^{mx} - 5me^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= 4m^2 - 5m \\\\\n		0 &= m(4m - 5) \\\\\n		m &= 0, \\frac{5}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two real distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1 + c_2e^{\\frac{5}{4}x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h\'(x) = \\frac{5}{4}c_2e^{\\frac{5}{4}x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(-2) &= c_1 + c_2e^{\\frac{5}{4}(-2)} = 0 \\\\\n		y_h\'(-2) &= \\frac{5}{4}c_2e^{\\frac{5}{4}(-2)} = 7\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom the second equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c_2 = \\frac{28}{5}e^{\\frac{5}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand from the first equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c_1 &= -c_2e^{-\\frac{5}{2}} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{28}{5}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = -\\frac{28}{5} + \\frac{28}{5}e^{\\frac{15}{4}x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(237,'Example_4',4,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 4y\' + 4y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the general solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 4y\' + 4y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 4me^{mx} + 4e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 4m + 4 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 2)^2 \\\\\n		m &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nto get one real value for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{2x} + c_2xe^{2x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(238,'Example_5',5,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 14y\' + 49y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(-4) = -1 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'(-4) = 5\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 14y\' + 49y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 14me^{mx} + 49e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 14m + 49 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 7)^2 \\\\\n		m &= -7\n	}$\n</div>\nto get one real value for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1e^{-7x} + c_2xe^{-7x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h\'(x) = -7c_1e^{-7x} + c_2e^{-7x} - 7c_2xe^{-7x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(-4) &= c_1e^{-7(-4)} + c_2(-4)e^{-7(-4)} = -1 \\\\\n		y_h\'(-4) &= -7c_1e^{-7(-4)} + c_2e^{-7(-4)} - 7c_2(-4)e^{-7(-4)} = 5\n	}$\n</div>\nThis can be rewritten in matrix form and using the inverse a solution can be obtained:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			e^{28} & -4e^{28} \\\\\n			-7e^{28} & 29e^{28}\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			c_1 \\\\\n			c_2\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-1 \\\\\n			5\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		\\begin{pmatrix}\n			c_1 \\\\\n			c_2\n		\\end{pmatrix} &= \\frac{1}{e^{56}} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			29e^{28} & 4e^{28} \\\\\n			7e^{28} & e^{28}\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-1 \\\\\n			5\n		\\end{pmatrix} \\\\\n		&= \\begin{pmatrix}\n			-9e^{-28} \\\\\n			-2e^{-28}\n		\\end{pmatrix}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = -9e^{-7x - 28} - 2xe^{-7x - 28}\n	}$\n</div>'),(239,'Example_6',6,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' - 8y\' + 16y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(0) = 1 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'(0) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 8y\' + 16y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 8me^{mx} + 16e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 8m + 16 \\\\\n		0 &= (m - 4)^2 \\\\\n		m &= 4\n	}$\n</div>\nto get one real value for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equatio