me that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' - 8y\' + 17y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} - 8me^{mx} + 17e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 - 8m + 17 \\\\\n		m &= \\frac{8 \\pm \\sqrt{64 - 68}}{2} \\\\\n		m &= 4 \\pm i\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two complex distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = e^{4x}[c_1\\cos(x) + c_2\\sin(x)]\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h\'(x) = 4e^{4x}[c_1\\cos(x) + c_2\\sin(x)] + e^{4x}[-c_1\\sin(x) + c_2\\cos(x)]\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(0) &= e^{4(0)}[c_1\\cos(0) + c_2\\sin(0)] = -4 \\\\\n		y_h\'(0) &= 4e^{4(0)}[c_1\\cos(0) + c_2\\sin(0)] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + e^{4(0)}[-c_1\\sin(0) + c_2\\cos(0)] = -1\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom these two equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c_1 &= -4 \\\\\n		c_2 &= 15\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{4x}[-4\\cos(x) + 15\\sin(x)]\n	}$\n</div>'),(242,'Example_9',9,92,'Given the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + 16y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) = -10 \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.5cm} y\'\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) = 3\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the particular solution.','Since this is a homogeneous linear constant coefficient equation the general solution will be given by the homogeneous solution. First we assume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = e^{mx}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= y\'\' + 16y \\\\\n		0 &= m^2e^{mx} + 16e^{mx} \\\\\n		0 &= m^2 + 16 \\\\\n		0 &= (m + 4i)(m - 4i) \\\\\n		m &= \\pm 4i\n	}$\n</div>\nto get two complex distinct values for $m$. With this the homogeneous solution is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h(x) = c_1\\cos(4x) + c_2\\sin(4x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h\'(x) = -4c_1\\sin(4x) + 4c_2\\cos(4x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the initial conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y_h\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) &= c_1\\cos\\Big( 4 \\cdot \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) + c_2\\sin\\Big( 4 \\cdot \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) = -10 \\\\\n		y_h\'\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) &= -4c_1\\sin\\Big( 4 \\cdot \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) + 4c_2\\cos\\Big( 4 \\cdot \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) = 3\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom these two equations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c_1 &= -10 \\\\\n		c_2 &= \\frac{3}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this the particular solution is written down as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = -10\\cos(4x) + \\frac{3}{4}\\sin(4x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(243,'Example_10',10,92,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = C \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.5cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R} \\setminus \\{ 0 \\}\n	}$\n</div>\nis a solution to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + k_1y\' + k_2y = 0\n	}$\n</div>\niff $k_2 = 0$.','Proving iff statements requires doing both directions. First if we assume that $k_2 = 0$, then the differential equation reduces down to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' + k_1y\' = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $y(x) = C$ is without a doubt a solution. Now if we assume that $y(x) = C$ is a solution, then when plugged in the differential equation reduces down to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k_2 \\cdot C = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWe began with the given information that $y(x) \\neq 0$, which tells us that $k_2 = 0$.'),(244,'Example_1',1,97,'',''),(245,'Example_2',2,97,'',''),(246,'Example_3',3,97,'',''),(247,'Ex