''),(281,'Example_8',8,100,'',''),(282,'Example_9',9,100,'',''),(283,'Example_10',10,100,'',''),(284,'Example_1',1,101,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 3x^2\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 3x^2 \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 3 \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^2 \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 3 \\cdot 2x \\\\\n		&= 6x\n	}$\n</div>'),(285,'Example_2',2,101,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 2x^\\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{4}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 2x^\\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{4}{x^2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2 \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^\\frac{1}{2} \\Big) + 4 \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^{-2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2 \\cdot \\frac{1}{2}x^{-\\frac{1}{2}} + 4 \\cdot -2x^{-3} \\\\\n		&= x^\\frac{1}{2} - 8x^{-3}\n	}$\n</div>'),(286,'Example_3',3,101,'Find the second derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^{\\pi + 1}\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} f(x) &= \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} x^{\\pi + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{d}{dx} x^{\\pi + 1} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( (\\pi + 1)x^{\\pi} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= (\\pi + 1)(\\pi)x^{\\pi - 1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(287,'Example_4',4,101,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{x^7 - 3}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{x^7 - 3}{x^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} (x^5 - 3x^{-2}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} x^5 - 3 \\frac{d}{dx} x^{-2} \\\\\n		&= 5x^4 + 6x^{-3}\n	}$\n</div>'),(288,'Example_5',5,101,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\ln(e^{2x})\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(e^{2x}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} (2x)\\ln(e) \\\\\n		&= 2 \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} x \\\\\n		&= 2\n	}$\n</div>'),(289,'Example_6',6,101,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{1}{\\pi x}\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{1}{\\pi x} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\pi} \\frac{d}{dx} x^{-1} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{x^{-2}}{\\pi} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{1}{\\pi x^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(290,'Example_7',7,101,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = (x + 1)(x - 1)\n	}$\n</div>','According to the power rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^n = nx^{n-1} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} (x + 1)(x - 1) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} (x^2 - 1) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} x^2 - \\frac{d}{dx} 1 \\\\\n		&= 2x\n	}$\n</div>'),(291,'Example_8',8,101,'Given that $p \\in \\mathbb{N}$, prove:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d^p}{dx^p} x^p = p!\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		p! = p(p - 1)(p - 2)\\dots(3)(2)(1)\n	}$\n</div>','Given the power rule, there are two ways to \"prove\". The formal way is to use induction since we are dealing with the natural numbers. In this scenario, the base case is going to occur when $p = 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x &= 1! \\\\\n		1 &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true. Now assuming the given statement, we move on to prove that it holds true for $p + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(p + 1)! &= \\frac{d^{p + 1}}{dx^{p + 1}} x^{p + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^p}{dx^p} \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} x^{p + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^p}{dx^p} (p + 1)x^p \\\\\n		&= (p + 1) \\frac{d^p}{dx^p} x^p \\\\\n		&= (p + 1)p! \\\\\n		&= (p + 1)!\n	}$\n</div>\nThe second method that I mentioned previously is more of a derivation rather than a proof. Assuming that we just want to determine the $p$th derivative of $f(x) = x^p$ we would calculate directly as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d^p}{dx^p} x^p \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p - 1}}{dx^{p - 1}} px^{p - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p - 2}}{dx^{p - 2}} p(p - 1)x^{p - 2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p - 3}}{dx^{p - 3}} p(p - 1)(p - 2)x^{p - 3} \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} p(p - 1)(p - 2)(p - 3)\\dots(3)(2) x \\\\\n		&= p(p - 1)(p - 2)(p - 3)\\dots(3)(2)(1) \\\\\n		&= p!\n	}$\n</div>'),(292,'Example_9',9,101,'Given that $p \\in \\mathbb{N}$, prove:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d^{p + 1}}{dx^{p + 1}} x^p = 0\n	}$\n</div>','Given the power rule, there are two ways to \"prove\". The formal way is to use induction since we are dealing with the natural numbers. In this scenario, the base case is going to occur when $p = 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} x &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} 1 &= 0 \\\\\n		0 &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true. Now assuming the given statement, we move on to prove that it holds true for $p + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\frac{d^{p + 2}}{dx^{p + 2}} x^{p + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p + 1}}{dx^{p + 1}} \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} x^{p + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p + 1}}{dx^{p + 1}} (p + 1)x^p \\\\\n		&= (p + 1) \\frac{d^{p + 1}}{dx^{p + 1}} x^p \\\\\n		&= (p + 1) \\cdot 0 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nThe second method that I mentioned previously is more of a derivation rather than a proof. Assuming that we just want to determine the $(p + 1)$th derivative of $f(x) = x^p$ we would calculate directly as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d^{p + 1}}{dx^{p + 1}} x^p \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^p}{dx^p} px^{p - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p - 1}}{dx^{p - 1}} p(p - 1)x^{p - 2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{p - 2}}{dx^{p - 2}} p(p - 1)(p - 2)x^{p - 3} \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} p(p - 1)(p - 2)(p - 3)\\dots(3)(2) x \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} p(p - 1)(p - 2)(p - 3)\\dots(3)(2)(1) \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(293,'Example_10',10,101,'Given that $p,r \\in \\mathbb{N}$, derive the following relation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d^r}{dx^r} x^p = \\mathcal{P}(p, r) x^{p - r}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{P}(p, r) = \\frac{p!}{(p - r)!}\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as a $r$-permutation of $p$ which represents the number of ordered arrangements of $r$ unique items selected out of a group containing $p$ total items.','Given the power rule we compute $r$ derivatives directly and simplify:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d^r}{dx^r} x^p \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{r - 1}}{dx^{r - 1}} px^{p - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{r - 2}}{dx^{r - 2}} p(p - 1)x^{p - 2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{r - 3}}{dx^{r - 3}} p(p - 1)(p - 2)x^{p - 3} \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} p(p - 1)\\dots(p - (r - 3))x^{p - (r - 2)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} p(p - 1)\\dots(p - (r - 2))x^{p - (r - 1)} \\\\\n		&= p\\dots(p - (r - 2))(p - (r - 1))x^{p - r} \\\\\n		&= p\\dots(p - (r - 1)) \\cdot \\frac{(p - r)\\dots(1)}{(p - r)\\dots(1)} x^{p - r} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{p!}{(p - r)!} x^{p - r} \\\\\n		&= \\mathcal{P}(p, r) x^{p - r}\n	}$\n</div>'),(294,'Example_1',1,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = 3x^2\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 3x^2\\sin(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 3x^2 \\Big) \\cdot \\sin(x) + 3x^2 \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 6x + \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(295,'Example_2',2,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\sin(x)\\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x)\\tan(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big) \\cdot \\tan(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sin(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\tan(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\cos(x)\\tan(x) + \\sin(x)\\sec^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(296,'Example_3',3,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = (5 + x^2)(7 + x + x^5)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( (5 + x^2)(7 + x + x^5) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 5 + x^2 \\Big) \\cdot (7 + x + x^5) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (5 + x^2) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 7 + x + x^5 \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2x(7 + x + x^5) + (5 + x^2)(1 + 5x^4)\n	}$\n</div>'),(297,'Example_4',4,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\sec(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\sec(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x)\\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big) \\cdot \\cos(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sin(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\cos^2(x) - \\sin^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(298,'Example_5',5,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\sin(2x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(2x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 2\\sin(x)\\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2 \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big) \\cdot \\cos(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 2\\sin(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2\\cos^2(x) - 2\\sin^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(299,'Example_6',6,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = (\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))\\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( (\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))\\tan(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( (\\sin(x) + \\cos(x)) \\Big) \\cdot \\tan(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (\\sin(x) + \\cos(x)) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\tan(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= (\\cos(x) - \\sin(x))\\tan(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))\\sec^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(300,'Example_7',7,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = x\\sin(x)\\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x\\sin(x)\\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x\\sin(x) \\Big) \\cdot \\cos(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + x\\sin(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x \\Big) \\cdot \\sin(x)\\cos(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + x\\cos(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big) - x\\sin^2(x) \\\\\n		&= (\\sin(x) + x\\cos(x))\\cos(x) - x\\sin^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(301,'Example_8',8,102,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = (x^2 + 1)\\sin(x)\\cot(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( (x^2 + 1)\\sin(x)\\cot(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( (x^2 + 1)\\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^2 + 1 \\Big) \\cdot \\cos(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + (x^2 + 1) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2x\\cos(x) - (x^2 + 1)\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(302,'Example_9',9,102,'Prove the following statement:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} &\\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) = \\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\\\\n		&\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} k \\in \\{ 1, 2, 3, \\dots, n \\}\n	}$\n</div>','This is nothing more than an extension to the product rule, one that handles the product of not just two functions, but rather $n$ of them. For a formal proof, consider using induction. For the base case let $n = 2$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\prod_{i = 1}^2 f_i(x) = \\sum_{i = 1}^2 f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true since we accept the standard product rule. Now we assume that given statement and try to show that it holds true for $n + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\sum_{i = 1}^{n + 1} f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\prod_{i = 1}^{n + 1} f_i(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\cdot f_{n + 1}(x) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot f_{n + 1}(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ f_{n + 1}(x) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) + \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\cdot f_{n + 1}\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^{n + 1} f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nWhile a formal proof is always important, it just as important to understand how the statement is derived. In this scenario we can derive the derivative of a product of $n$ functions by recursively using the standard product rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 1} f_i(x) \\cdot f_n(x) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 1} f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot f_n(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 1} f_i(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ f_n(x) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 1} f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot f_n(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + f_n\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq n} f_i(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 2} f_i(x) \\cdot f_{n - 1}(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot f_n(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + f_n\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq n} f_i(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 2} f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot f_{n - 1}(x)f_n(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + f_{n - 1}\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq n - 1} f_i(x) + f_n\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq n} f_i(x) \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{2} f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot \\prod_{k \\neq 1,2} f_k \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sum_{i = 3}^n f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^{1} f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\cdot \\prod_{k \\neq 1} f_k \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sum_{i = 2}^n f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(303,'Example_10',10,102,'Given that $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are two differentiable functions, prove the $\\textit{General Leibniz Rule}$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d^n}{dx^n} (fg) = \\sum_{i = 0}^n {n \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n - i)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		{n \\choose i} = \\frac{n!}{i!(n - i)!}\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as the $\\textit{binomial coefficient}$.','This is nothing more than an extension to the product rule, one that handles not the first derivative, but rather the $n$th derivative. For a formal proof, consider using induction. For the base case let $n = 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (fg) &= \\sum_{i = 0}^1 {1 \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n - 1)} \\\\\n		f\'g + fg\' &= {1 \\choose 0} f^{(0)}g^{(1)} + {1 \\choose 1}f^{(1)}g^{(0)} \\\\\n		f\'g + fg\' &= fg\' + f\'g \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true since we accept the standard product rule. Now we assume that given statement and try to show that it holds true for $n + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\sum_{i = 0}^{n + 1} {n + 1 \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n + 1}}{dx^{n + 1}} (fg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^n}{dx^n} \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} (fg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^n}{dx^n} (f\'g + fg\') \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^n}{dx^n} (f^{(1)}g) + \\frac{d^n}{dx^n} (fg^{(1)}) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 0}^n {n \\choose i} f^{(i + 1)}g^{(n - i)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sum_{i = 0}^n {n \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^{n + 1} {n \\choose i - 1} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sum_{i = 0}^n {n \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		&= f^{(n + 1)}g^{(0)} + \\sum_{i = 1}^{n} {n \\choose i - 1} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\sum_{i = 1}^n {n \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} + f^{(0)}g^{(n + 1)} \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^n \\Bigg[ {n \\choose i} + {n \\choose i - 1} \\Bigg] f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + f^{(n + 1)}g^{(0)} + f^{(0)}g^{(n + 1)} \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^n {n + 1 \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + {n + 1 \\choose n + 1} f^{(n + 1)}g^{(0)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + {n + 1 \\choose 0} f^{(0)}g^{(n + 1)} \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 0}^{n + 1} {n + 1 \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n + 1 - i)}\n	}$\n</div>\nWhile a formal proof is always important, it just as important to understand how the statement is derived. In this scenario we can derive the $n$th derivative of a product of two functions by recursively using the standard product rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d^n}{dx^n} (fg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 1}}{dx^{n - 1}} (f^{(1)}g^{(0)} + f^{(0)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 1}}{dx^{n - 1}} (f^{(1)}g^{(0)}) + \\frac{d^{n - 1}}{dx^{n - 1}} (f^{(0)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(2)}g^{(0)} + f^{(1)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(1)}g^{(1)} + f^{(0)}g^{(2)}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(2)}g^{(0)}) + \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(1)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(1)}g^{(1)}) + \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(0)}g^{(2)}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(2)}g^{(0)}) + 2\\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(1)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{d^{n - 2}}{dx^{n - 2}} (f^{(0)}g^{(2)}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(3)}g^{(0)} + f^{(2)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 2\\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(2)}g^{(1)} + f^{(1)}g^{(2)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(1)}g^{(2)} + f^{(0)}g^{(3)}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(3)}g^{(0)}) + 3\\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(2)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3\\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(1)}g^{(2)}) + \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(0)}g^{(3)}) \\\\\n		&= {3 \\choose 3} \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(3)}g^{(0)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + {3 \\choose 2} \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(2)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + {3 \\choose 1} \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(1)}g^{(2)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + {3 \\choose 0} \\frac{d^{n - 3}}{dx^{n - 3}} (f^{(0)}g^{(3)}) \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		&= {n \\choose n} (f^{(n)}g^{(0)}) + {n \\choose n - 1} (f^{(n - 1)}g^{(1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\dots + {n \\choose 1} (f^{(1)}g^{(n - 1)}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + {n \\choose 0} \\frac{d}{dx} (f^{(0)}g^{(n)}) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 0}^n {n \\choose i} f^{(i)}g^{(n - i)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(304,'Example_1',1,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{2x}{\\sin(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{2x}{\\sin(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 2x \\Big) \\cdot \\sin(x) - 2x \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big)}{\\sin^2(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2\\sin(x) - 2x\\cos(x)}{\\sin^2(x)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(305,'Example_2',2,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\tan(x) \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\cos(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big)\' \\cdot \\cos(x) - \\sin(x) \\cdot \\Big( \\cos(x) \\Big)\'}{\\cos^2(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\cos^2(x) + \\sin^2(x)}{\\cos^2(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\cos^2(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\sec^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(306,'Example_3',3,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{e^x}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{e^x}{x^2} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( e^x \\Big) \\cdot x^2 - e^x \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^2 \\Big)}{x^4} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{x^2e^x - 2xe^x}{x^4}\n	}$\n</div>'),(307,'Example_4',4,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\sec(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\sec(x) \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{1}{\\cos(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 1 \\Big) \\cdot \\cos(x) - 1 \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\cos(x) \\Big)}{\\cos^2(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\cos^2(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\sin(x)}{\\cos(x)} \\cdot \\frac{1}{\\cos(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\tan(x)\\sec(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(308,'Example_5',5,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{x^7 + 1}{x^2 + 3}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{x^7 + 1}{x^2 + 3} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\Big( x^7 + 1 \\Big)\' (x^2 + 3) - (x^7 + 1) \\Big( x^2 + 3 \\Big)\'}{(x^2 + 3)^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{7x^6(x^2 + 3) - 2x(x^7 + 1)}{(x^2 + 3)^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(309,'Example_6',6,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{\\tan(x)}{\\sin(x) + \\cos(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{\\tan(x)}{\\sin(x) + \\cos(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\Big( \\tan(x) \\Big)\' (\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))}{(\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))^2} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{\\tan(x) \\Big( \\sin(x) + \\cos(x) \\Big)\'}{(\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))\\sec^2(x)}{(\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))^2} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{(\\cos(x) - \\sin(x))\\tan(x)}{(\\sin(x) + \\cos(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(310,'Example_7',7,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{2x}{(x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{2x}{(x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\Big( 2x \\Big)\' (x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4)}{((x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4))^2} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{2x \\Big( (x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4) \\Big)\'}{((x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4))^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2(x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4)}{((x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4))^2} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{4x^2(x^3 + x^2 - 4)}{((x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4))^2} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{2x(x^2 + 1)(3x^2 + 2x)}{((x^2 + 1)(x^3 + x^2 - 4))^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(311,'Example_8',8,103,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\csc(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\csc(x) \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\frac{1}{\\sin(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( 1 \\Big) \\cdot \\sin(x) - 1 \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\sin(x) \\Big)}{(\\sin(x))^2} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{\\cos(x)}{(\\sin(x))^2} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{\\cos(x)}{\\sin(x)} \\cdot \\frac{1}{\\sin(x)} \\\\\n		&= -\\cot(x)\\csc(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(312,'Example_9',9,103,'Derive the following relationship:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\Bigg]^{-1} = -\\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i\'(x) \\Bigg[ \\sum_{j = 1}^n f_j(x) \\Bigg]^{-2}\n	}$\n</div>\nassuming that for all values of $i$, each $f_i(x)$ is differentiable at $x$ and the total sum does not equate to zero.','To tackle this it might be easier if we first set the denominator to be a single function so that the derivative is right away given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{1}{h(x)} = -\\frac{h\'(x)}{(h(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhen using the quotient rule. Now it is just a simple task of determining the derivative of the denominator, which is a rather trivial task since the derivative is a linear operator:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&-h\'(x)(h(x))^{-2} \\\\\n		&= -\\Bigg[ \\frac{d}{dx} \\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\Bigg] \\Bigg[ \\sum_{j = 1}^n f_i(x) \\Bigg]^{-2} \\\\\n		&= -\\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i\'(x) \\Bigg[ \\sum_{j = 1}^n f_j(x) \\Bigg]^{-2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(313,'Example_10',10,103,'Derive the following relationship:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i(x) \\Bigg]^{-1} = -\\sum_{i = 1}^n \\frac{f_i\'(x)}{f_i^2(x)} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\Bigg]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nassuming that for all values of $i$, each $f_i(x) \\neq 0$ and is differentiable at $x$.','To tackle this it might be easier if we first set the denominator to be a single function so that the derivative is right away given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{1}{h(x)} = -\\frac{h\'(x)}{(h(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhen using the quotient rule. Now it is just a simple task of determining the derivative of the denominator. Fortunately we have already covered this before in Example 9 for the product rule, which provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&-h\'(x)(h(x))^{-2} \\\\\n		&= -\\Bigg[ \\sum_{i = 1}^n f_i\'(x) \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\Bigg] \\Bigg[ \\prod_{i = 1}^n f_i^2(x) \\Bigg]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= -\\sum_{i = 1}^n \\frac{f_i\'(x)}{f_1^2(x)\\dots f_{n - 1}^2(x)f_n^2(x)} \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\\\\n		&= -\\sum_{i = 1}^n \\frac{f_i\'(x)}{f_i^2(x)} \\Bigg[ \\prod_{k \\neq i} f_k(x) \\Bigg]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(314,'Example_1',1,104,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\sin(2x)\n	}$\n</div>','According to the chain rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(g(x)) = \\frac{df}{dg} \\cdot \\frac{dg}{dx}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we identify our components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(g) &= \\sin(g) \\\\\n		g(x) &= 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( \\sin(2x) \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\Big( \\cos(2x) \\Big) \\cdot \\Big( 2 \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 2\\cos(2x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(315,'Example_2',2,104,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = (x^9 - x^7 + 4x - 3)^{100}\n	}$\n</div>','According to the chain rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(g(x)) = \\frac{df}{dg} \\cdot \\frac{dg}{dx}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we identify our components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(g) &= g^{100} \\\\\n		g(x) &= x^9 - x^7 + 4x - 3\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( (x^9 - x^7 + 4x - 3)^{100} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= 100(9x^8 - 7x^6 + 4)(x^9 - x^7 + 4x - 3)^{99}\n	}$\n</div>'),(316,'Example_3',3,104,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = e^{x^7}e^{\\sin(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','According to the chain rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(g(x)) = \\frac{df}{dg} \\cdot \\frac{dg}{dx}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we identify our components as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(g) &= e^g \\\\\n		g(x) &= x^7 + \\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( e^{x^7}e^{\\sin(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( e^{x^7 + \\sin(x)} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\Big( e^{x^7 + \\sin(x)} \\Big) \\cdot \\Big( 7x^6 + \\cos(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= (7x^6 + \\cos(x))e^{x^7 + \\sin(x)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(317,'Example_4',4,104,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = f(g(k(x)))\n	}$\n</div>','According to the chain rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(g(x)) = \\frac{df}{dg} \\cdot \\frac{dg}{dx}\n	}$\n</div>\nso:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} h(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Bigg( f(g(k(x))) \\Bigg) \\\\\n		&= \\Big( f\'(g(k(x))) \\Big) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( g(k(x)) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\Big( f\'(g(k(x))) \\Big) \\cdot \\Big( g\'(k(x)) \\Big) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( k(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		&= f\'(g(k(x)))g\'(k(x))k\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(318,'Example_5',5,104,'Prove the following identity:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_1(f_2(f_3(\\dots f_{n - 1}(f_n(f_{n + 1})))) = \\prod_{i = 1}^n \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}}\n	}$\n</div>\nassuming that for each value of $i$, $f_i(x)$ is differentiable at $f_{i + 1}(x)$.','This is nothing more than an extension to the chain rule, one that handles the composition of not just two functions, but rather $n + 1$ of them. For a formal proof, consider using induction. For the base case let $n = 2$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{df_3} f_1(f_2(f_3)) &= \\prod_{i = 1}^2 \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}} \\\\\n		\\frac{df_1}{df_2} \\cdot \\frac{df_2}{df_3} &= \\frac{df_1}{df_2} \\cdot \\frac{df_2}{df_3}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true since we accept the standard chain rule. Now we assume that given statement and try to show that it holds true for $n + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{df_{n + 2}} f_1(f_2(f_3(\\dots f_{n + 1}(f_{n + 2})))) \\\\\n		&= \\prod_{i = 1}^{n + 1} \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}} \\\\\n		&= \\prod_{i = 1}^n \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}} \\cdot \\frac{df_{n + 1}}{df_{n + 2}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_1(\\dots f_{n - 1}(f_n(f_{n + 1}))) \\cdot \\frac{df_{n + 1}}{df_{n + 2}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{df_{n + 2}} f_1(f_2(f_3(\\dots f_{n + 1}(f_{n + 2}))))\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the last step involves reversing the standard chain rule. While a formal proof is always important, it just as important to understand how the statement is derived. In this scenario we can derive the derivative of a composition of $n + 1$ functions by recursively using the standard chain rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_1(f_2(f_3(\\dots f_{n - 1}(f_n(f_{n + 1})))) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{df_1}{df_2} \\cdot \\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_2(f_3(\\dots f_n(f_{n + 1}))) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{df_1}{df_2} \\cdot \\frac{df_2}{df_3} \\cdot \\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_3(\\dots f_n(f_{n + 1})) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{df_1}{df_2} \\cdot \\frac{df_2}{df_3} \\cdot \\frac{df_3}{df_4} \\cdot \\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_4(\\dots f_n(f_{n + 1})) \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		&= \\prod_{i = 1}^{n - 1} \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}} \\cdot \\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_n(f_{n + 1}) \\\\\n		&= \\prod_{i = 1}^n \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}} \\cdot \\frac{d}{df_{n + 1}} f_{n + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\prod_{i = 1}^n \\frac{df_i}{df_{i + 1}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(319,'Example_6',6,104,'You are given the following information:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$x$</td>\n		    <td>$f(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$7$</td>\n		    <td>$5$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-2$</td>\n		    <td>$-1$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-4$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nDetermine the values of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(3) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} (f^{-1})\'(7)\n	}$\n</div>','Given a function, $f(x)$, we can determine the derivative of its inverse according to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) = \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(3) &= \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(3))} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{f\'(2)} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{1}{4} \\\\\n		(f^{-1})\'(7) &= \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(7))} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{f\'(0)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{5}\n	}$\n</div>'),(320,'Example_7',7,104,'Determine the derivative of $h(x) = \\ln(x)$ without using the fact that $h\'(x) = \\frac{1}{x}$. This essentially means that the standard limit process will not work since it would require $\\textit{L\'Hospital\'s Rule}$ which uses the derivative. You are allowed to use the fact that $h^{-1}(x) = e^x$ and that $(h^{-1})\'(x) = e^x$.','Given a function, $f(x)$, we can determine the derivative of its inverse according to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) = \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= e^x \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= e^x \\\\\n		f^{-1}(x) &= \\ln(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich when plugged in provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(x) &= \\frac{1}{e^{\\ln(x)}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(321,'Example_8',8,104,'Prove that the derivative of $h(x) = \\arctan(x)$ is in fact $h\'(x) = \\frac{1}{1 + x^2}$.','Given a function, $f(x)$, we can determine the derivative of its inverse according to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) = \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= \\tan(x) \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= \\sec^2(x) \\\\\n		f^{-1}(x) &= \\arctan(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich when plugged in provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\arctan(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sec^2(\\arctan(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo simplify the denominator, begin by setting:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\theta = \\arctan(x) \\implies \\tan(\\theta) = x\n	}$\n</div>\nIf you draw out a right triangle and label one of the angles as $\\theta$, then opposite the angle is side with length $x$ and adjacent the angle is side with length 1. Using the $\\textit{Pythagorean Theorem}$, the hypotenuse is $\\sqrt{1 + x^2}$. Now to determine the rest:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sec(\\theta) &= \\frac{\\text{hypotenuse}}{\\text{adjacent}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\sqrt{1 + x^2}}{1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich simplifies the derivative down to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\arctan(x) = \\frac{1}{1 + x^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(322,'Example_9',9,104,'Prove that the derivative of $h(x) = \\arcsin(x)$ is in fact $h\'(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$.','Given a function, $f(x)$, we can determine the derivative of its inverse according to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) = \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nso we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= \\sin(x) \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= \\cos(x) \\\\\n		f^{-1}(x) &= \\arcsin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich when plugged in provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\arcsin(x) = \\frac{1}{\\cos(\\arcsin(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo simplify the denominator, begin by setting:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\theta = \\arcsin(x) \\implies \\sin(\\theta) = x\n	}$\n</div>\nIf you draw out a right triangle and label one of the angles as $\\theta$, then opposite the angle is side with length $x$ and hypotenuse with length 1. Using the $\\textit{Pythagorean Theorem}$, the adjacent side is $\\sqrt{1 - x^2}$. Now to determine the rest:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\cos(\\theta) &= \\frac{\\text{adjacent}}{\\text{hypotenuse}} \\\\\n		&= \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich simplifies the derivative down to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\arcsin(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(323,'Example_10',10,104,'Determine a formula to compute $(f^{-1})\'\'(x)$ given that we know $f(x)$, $f\'(x)$, $f\'\'(x)$, $f^{-1}(x)$, and $(f^{-1})\'(x)$ are all differentiable at $x$.','We already know that the first derivative of the inverse is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) = \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich can now be used to determine a formula for the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&(f^{-1})\'\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} (f\'(f^{-1}(x)))^{-1} \\\\\n		&= -(f\'(f^{-1}(x)))^{-2} \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} f\'(f^{-1}(x)) \\\\\n		&= -(f\'(f^{-1}(x)))^{-2} f\'\'(f^{-1}(x)) (f^{-1})\'(x) \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{f\'\'(f^{-1}(x))(f^{-1})\'(x)}{(f\'(f^{-1}(x)))^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(324,'Example_1',1,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere you are given the graph of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Introduction/Example_1.png\">\n</div>','Observing the graph shows that from the left side the function approaches 1, but from the right side approaches -6. Since these two are not equal:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} f(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(325,'Example_2',2,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere you are given the graph of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Introduction/Example_2.png\">\n</div>','Observing the graph shows that from both the left and right sides the function approaches 1. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x) = 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(326,'Example_3',3,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^3 - 8}{x - 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing a numerical approach.','First the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$1.900$</td>\n		    <td>$11.410$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$1.990$</td>\n		    <td>$11.940$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$1.999$</td>\n		    <td>$11.994$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$2.001$</td>\n		    <td>$12.006$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$2.010$</td>\n		    <td>$12.060$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$2.100$</td>\n		    <td>$12.610$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^3 - 8}{x - 2} = 12\n	}$\n</div>'),(327,'Example_4',4,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( \\frac{2}{e^x - 1} - \\frac{2}{x} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nusing a numerical approach.','First the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.017$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.002$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.998$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.983$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( \\frac{2}{e^x - 1} - \\frac{2}{x} \\Big) = -1\n	}$\n</div>'),(328,'Example_5',5,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 3} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere you are given the graph of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Introduction/Example_5.png\">\n</div>','Observing the graph shows that from both the left and right sides the function approaches 3. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 3} f(x) = 3\n	}$\n</div>'),(329,'Example_6',6,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \n		f(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			-x + 1 & x < 0 \\\\\n			10 & x = 0 \\\\\n			x + 1 & x > 0\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing a numerical approach.','First the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$1.100$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$1.010$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$1.001$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$1.001$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$1.010$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$1.100$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x) = 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(330,'Example_7',7,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{x^2 - 2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing an analytical approach.','By simplifying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{x^2 - 2x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{(x - 2)(x + 6)}{x(x - 2)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x + 6}{x} \\\\\n		&= 4\n	}$\n</div>'),(331,'Example_8',8,108,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{x - \\sqrt{3x + 4}}{4 - x}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing an analytical approach.','By simplifying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{x - \\sqrt{3x + 4}}{4 - x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{x - \\sqrt{3x + 4}}{4 - x} \\cdot \\frac{x + \\sqrt{3x + 4}}{t + \\sqrt{3x + 4}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{x^2 - 3x - 4}{(4 - x)(x + \\sqrt{3x + 4})} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{(x - 4)(x + 1)}{-(x - 4)(x + \\sqrt{3x + 4})} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} -\\frac{x + 1}{x + \\sqrt{3x + 4}} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{5}{8}\n	}$\n</div>'),(332,'Example_9',9,108,'Given $a,b \\in \\mathbb{R}$, evaluate both expressions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing an analytical approach where interchanging the limits is strictly prohibited. Do you get the same value for both limits? If not, discuss the numerical nature of $\\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}$.','The first expression provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} &= \\lim_{a \\rightarrow infty} \\Big( \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} 0 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhile the second expression gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} &= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\Big( \\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\infty \\\\\n		&= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nif $b > 0$, otherwise:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} &= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} \\Big( \\lim_{a \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{a}{b} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow \\infty} -\\infty \\\\\n		&= -\\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nAfter evaluation it becomes clear that these two expressions approach different values even though they both go to $\\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}$. It is exactly because of this that $\\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}$ is called an indeterminate form since it cannot take on one specific numerical value.'),(333,'Example_10',10,108,'Given $a,b \\neq 0$, evaluate both expressions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} a^b \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} a^b\n	}$\n</div>\nusing an analytical approach where interchanging the limits is strictly prohibited. Do you get the same value for both limits? If not, discuss the numerical nature of $0^0$.','The first expression provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} a^b &= \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} a^b \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} a^0 \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} 1 \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhile the second expression gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} a^b &= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} a^b \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} 0^b \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} 0 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nif $b > 0$, otherwise:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} a^b &= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( \\lim_{a \\rightarrow 0} a^b \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\infty \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{b \\rightarrow 0} \\infty \\\\\n		&= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nAfter evaluation it becomes clear that these two expressions approach different values even though they both go to $0^0$. It is exactly because of this that $0^0$ is called an indeterminate form since it cannot take on one specific numerical value.'),(334,'Example_1',1,109,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			\\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{x^2 - 2x} & x \\neq 2 \\\\\n			6 & x = 2\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^-} g(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^+} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nusing a numerical approach. After having found the results for the above, what can be said of the limit as $x \\rightarrow 2$?','From the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$1.900$</td>\n		    <td>$4.158$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$1.990$</td>\n		    <td>$4.015$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$1.999$</td>\n		    <td>$4.002$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$2.001$</td>\n		    <td>$3.999$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$2.010$</td>\n		    <td>$3.985$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$2.100$</td>\n		    <td>$3.857$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwe have enough evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^-} g(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^+} g(x) = 4\n	}$\n</div>\nthus giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} g(x) = 4\